cli/README.md
     1‚Üí# Command-line tool
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe `mdbook` command-line tool is used to create and build books.
     4‚ÜíAfter you have [installed](../guide/installation.md) `mdbook`, you can run the `mdbook help` command in your terminal to view the available commands.
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíThis following sections provide in-depth information on the different commands available.
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí* [`mdbook init <directory>`](init.md) --- Creates a new book with minimal boilerplate to start with.
     9‚Üí* [`mdbook build`](build.md) --- Renders the book.
    10‚Üí* [`mdbook watch`](watch.md) --- Rebuilds the book any time a source file changes.
    11‚Üí* [`mdbook serve`](serve.md) --- Runs a web server to view the book, and rebuilds on changes.
    12‚Üí* [`mdbook test`](test.md) --- Tests Rust code samples.
    13‚Üí* [`mdbook clean`](clean.md) --- Deletes the rendered output.
    14‚Üí* [`mdbook completions`](completions.md) --- Support for shell auto-completion.
cli/arg-watcher.md
     1‚Üí#### `--watcher`
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThere are different backends used to determine when a file has changed.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí* `poll` (default) --- Checks for file modifications by scanning the filesystem every second.
     6‚Üí* `native` --- Uses the native operating system facilities to receive notifications when files change.
     7‚Üí  This can have less constant overhead, but may not be as reliable as the `poll` based watcher. See these issues for more information: [#383](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/383) [#1441](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/1441) [#1707](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/1707) [#2035](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/2035) [#2102](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/2102)
cli/build.md
     1‚Üí# The build command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe build command is used to render your book:
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí```bash
     6‚Üímdbook build
     7‚Üí```
     8‚Üí
     9‚ÜíIt will try to parse your `SUMMARY.md` file to understand the structure of your
    10‚Üíbook and fetch the corresponding files. Note that this will also create files
    11‚Üímentioned in `SUMMARY.md` which are not yet present.
    12‚Üí
    13‚ÜíThe rendered output will maintain the same directory structure as the source for
    14‚Üíconvenience. Large books will therefore remain structured when rendered.
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    17‚Üí
    18‚ÜíThe `build` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    19‚Üíroot instead of the current working directory.
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí```bash
    22‚Üímdbook build path/to/book
    23‚Üí```
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí#### `--open`
    26‚Üí
    27‚ÜíWhen you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    28‚Üíyour default web browser after building it.
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí#### `--dest-dir`
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíThe `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    33‚Üíbook. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    34‚Üínot specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    35‚Üí`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí-------------------
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí***Note:*** *The build command copies all files (excluding files with `.md` extension) from the source directory
    40‚Üíinto the build directory.*
cli/clean.md
     1‚Üí# The clean command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe clean command is used to delete the generated book and any other build
     4‚Üíartifacts.
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üí```bash
     7‚Üímdbook clean
     8‚Üí```
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíThe `clean` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    13‚Üíroot instead of the current working directory.
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí```bash
    16‚Üímdbook clean path/to/book
    17‚Üí```
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üí#### `--dest-dir`
    20‚Üí
    21‚ÜíThe `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to override the book's output
    22‚Üídirectory, which will be deleted by this command. Relative paths are interpreted
    23‚Üírelative to the current directory. If not specified it will default to the
    24‚Üívalue of the `build.build-dir` key in `book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí```bash
    27‚Üímdbook clean --dest-dir=path/to/book
    28‚Üí```
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí`path/to/book` could be absolute or relative.
cli/completions.md
     1‚Üí# The completions command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4‚ÜíThis means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíThe completions first need to be installed for your shell:
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí```bash
     9‚Üí# bash
    10‚Üímdbook completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/mdbook
    11‚Üí# oh-my-zsh
    12‚Üímdbook completions zsh > ~/.oh-my-zsh/completions/_mdbook
    13‚Üíautoload -U compinit && compinit
    14‚Üí```
    15‚Üí
    16‚ÜíThe command prints a completion script for the given shell.
    17‚ÜíRun `mdbook completions --help` for a list of supported shells.
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíWhere to place the completions depend on which shell you are using and your operating system.
    20‚ÜíConsult your shell's documentation for more information one where to place the script.
cli/init.md
     1‚Üí# The init command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThere is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4‚Üíthis purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíThe `init` command is used like this:
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí```bash
     9‚Üímdbook init
    10‚Üí```
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíWhen using the `init` command for the first time, a couple of files will be set
    13‚Üíup for you:
    14‚Üí```bash
    15‚Üíbook-test/
    16‚Üí‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ book
    17‚Üí‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src
    18‚Üí    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ chapter_1.md
    19‚Üí    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ SUMMARY.md
    20‚Üí```
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí- The `src` directory is where you write your book in markdown. It contains all
    23‚Üí  the source files, configuration files, etc.
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí- The `book` directory is where your book is rendered. All the output is ready
    26‚Üí  to be uploaded to a server to be seen by your audience.
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí- The `SUMMARY.md` is the skeleton of your
    29‚Üí  book, and is discussed in more detail [in another
    30‚Üí  chapter](../format/summary.md).
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md
    33‚Üí
    34‚ÜíWhen a `SUMMARY.md` file already exists, the `init` command will first parse it
    35‚Üíand generate the missing files according to the paths used in the `SUMMARY.md`.
    36‚ÜíThis allows you to think and create the whole structure of your book and then
    37‚Üílet mdBook generate it for you.
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    40‚Üí
    41‚ÜíThe `init` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    42‚Üíinstead of the current working directory.
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí```bash
    45‚Üímdbook init path/to/book
    46‚Üí```
    47‚Üí
    48‚Üí#### `--theme`
    49‚Üí
    50‚ÜíWhen you use the `--theme` flag, the default theme will be copied into a
    51‚Üídirectory called `theme` in your source directory so that you can modify it.
    52‚Üí
    53‚ÜíThe theme is selectively overwritten, this means that if you don't want to
    54‚Üíoverwrite a specific file, just delete it and the default file will be used.
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí#### `--title`
    57‚Üí
    58‚ÜíSpecify a title for the book. If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask for 
    59‚Üía title. 
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üí```bash
    62‚Üímdbook init --title="my amazing book"
    63‚Üí```
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí#### `--ignore`
    66‚Üí
    67‚ÜíCreate a `.gitignore` file configured to ignore the `book` directory created when [building] a book. 
    68‚ÜíIf not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask whether it should be created.
    69‚Üí
    70‚Üí```bash
    71‚Üímdbook init --ignore=none
    72‚Üí```
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí```bash
    75‚Üímdbook init --ignore=git
    76‚Üí```
    77‚Üí
    78‚Üí[building]: build.md
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí#### `--force`
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíSkip the prompts to create a `.gitignore` and for the title for the book.
cli/serve.md
     1‚Üí# The serve command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4‚Üí`localhost:3000` by default: 
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üí```bash
     7‚Üímdbook serve
     8‚Üí```
     9‚Üí
    10‚ÜíThe `serve` command  watches the book's `src` directory for
    11‚Üíchanges, rebuilding the book and refreshing clients for each change; this includes
    12‚Üíre-creating deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`! A websocket
    13‚Üíconnection is used to trigger the client-side refresh.
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí***Note:*** *The `serve` command is for testing a book's HTML output, and is not
    16‚Üíintended to be a complete HTTP server for a website.*
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    19‚Üí
    20‚ÜíThe `serve` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    21‚Üíroot instead of the current working directory.
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí```bash
    24‚Üímdbook serve path/to/book
    25‚Üí```
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí### Server options
    28‚Üí
    29‚ÜíThe `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí```bash
    32‚Üímdbook serve path/to/book -p 8000 -n 127.0.0.1 
    33‚Üí```
    34‚Üí
    35‚Üí#### `--open`
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíWhen you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the book in your
    38‚Üídefault web browser after starting the server.
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí#### `--dest-dir`
    41‚Üí
    42‚ÜíThe `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    43‚Üíbook. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    44‚Üínot specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    45‚Üí`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí{{#include arg-watcher.md}}
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üí#### Specify exclude patterns
    50‚Üí
    51‚ÜíThe `serve` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    52‚Üíthe `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    53‚Üícontain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    54‚Üídocumentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    55‚Üíignoring temporary files created by some editors.
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí***Note:*** *Only the `.gitignore` from the book root directory is used. Global
    58‚Üí`$HOME/.gitignore` or `.gitignore` files in parent directories are not used.*
cli/test.md
     1‚Üí# The test command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíWhen writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4‚Üí[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5‚Üíof code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6‚Üíthem to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7‚Üí
     8‚ÜímdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9‚Üíthe moment, only Rust tests are supported.
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí#### Disable tests on a code block
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üírustdoc doesn't test code blocks which contain the `ignore` attribute:
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí    ```rust,ignore
    16‚Üí    fn main() {}
    17‚Üí    ```
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üírustdoc also doesn't test code blocks which specify a language other than Rust:
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí    ```markdown
    22‚Üí    **Foo**: _bar_
    23‚Üí    ```
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üírustdoc *does* test code blocks which have no language specified:
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí    ```
    28‚Üí    This is going to cause an error!
    29‚Üí    ```
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    32‚Üí
    33‚ÜíThe `test` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    34‚Üíinstead of the current working directory.
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí```bash
    37‚Üímdbook test path/to/book
    38‚Üí```
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí#### `--library-path`
    41‚Üí
    42‚ÜíThe `--library-path` (`-L`) option allows you to add directories to the library
    43‚Üísearch path used by `rustdoc` when it builds and tests the examples. Multiple
    44‚Üídirectories can be specified with multiple options (`-L foo -L bar`) or with a
    45‚Üícomma-delimited list (`-L foo,bar`). The path should point to the Cargo
    46‚Üí[build cache](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/guide/build-cache.html) `deps` directory that
    47‚Üícontains the build output of your project. For example, if your Rust project's book is in a directory
    48‚Üínamed `my-book`, the following command would include the crate's dependencies when running `test`:
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí```shell
    51‚Üímdbook test my-book -L target/debug/deps/
    52‚Üí```
    53‚Üí
    54‚ÜíSee the `rustdoc` command-line [documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/command-line-arguments.html#-l--library-path-where-to-look-for-dependencies)
    55‚Üífor more information.
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí#### `--chapter`
    58‚Üí
    59‚ÜíThe `--chapter` (`-c`) option allows you to test a specific chapter of the
    60‚Üíbook using the chapter name or the relative path to the chapter.
cli/watch.md
     1‚Üí# The watch command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4‚Üífile change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5‚Üíchanged. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6‚Üíbuild automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7‚Üídeleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíThe `watch` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    12‚Üíroot instead of the current working directory.
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí```bash
    15‚Üímdbook watch path/to/book
    16‚Üí```
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí#### `--open`
    19‚Üí
    20‚ÜíWhen you use the `--open` (`-o`) option, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    21‚Üíyour default web browser.
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí#### `--dest-dir`
    24‚Üí
    25‚ÜíThe `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    26‚Üíbook. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    27‚Üínot specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    28‚Üí`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí{{#include arg-watcher.md}}
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí#### Specify exclude patterns
    33‚Üí
    34‚ÜíThe `watch` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    35‚Üíthe `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    36‚Üícontain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    37‚Üídocumentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    38‚Üíignoring temporary files created by some editors.
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí_Note: Only `.gitignore` from book root directory is used. Global
    41‚Üí`$HOME/.gitignore` or `.gitignore` files in parent directories are not used._
continuous-integration.md
     1‚Üí# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThere are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíThe following provides some general guidelines on how to configure your service to run mdBook.
     6‚ÜíSpecific recipes can be found at the [Automated Deployment] wiki page.
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí[GitHub Actions]: https://docs.github.com/en/actions
     9‚Üí[GitLab CI/CD]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/
    10‚Üí[Automated Deployment]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Automated-Deployment
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí## Installing mdBook
    13‚Üí
    14‚ÜíThere are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15‚ÜíThe particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí### Pre-compiled binaries
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíPerhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20‚ÜíA simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí```sh
    23‚Üímkdir bin
    24‚Üícurl -sSL https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases/download/{{ mdbook-version }}/mdbook-{{ mdbook-version }}-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz | tar -xz --directory=bin
    25‚Üíbin/mdbook build
    26‚Üí```
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíSome considerations for this approach:
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí* This is relatively fast, and does not necessarily require dealing with caching.
    31‚Üí* This does not require installing Rust.
    32‚Üí* Specifying a specific URL means you have to manually update your script to get a new version.
    33‚Üí  This may be a benefit if you want to lock to a specific version.
    34‚Üí  However, some users prefer to automatically get a newer version when they are published.
    35‚Üí* You are reliant on the GitHub CDN being available.
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí[releases]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí### Building from source
    40‚Üí
    41‚ÜíBuilding from source will require having Rust installed.
    42‚ÜíSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    43‚Üí
    44‚ÜíAfter Rust is installed, `cargo install` can be used to build and install mdBook.
    45‚ÜíWe recommend using a SemVer version specifier so that you get the latest **non-breaking** version of mdBook.
    46‚ÜíFor example:
    47‚Üí
    48‚Üí```sh
    49‚Üícargo install mdbook --no-default-features --features search --vers "^0.4" --locked
    50‚Üí```
    51‚Üí
    52‚ÜíThis includes several recommended options:
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí* `--no-default-features` --- Disables features like the HTTP server used by `mdbook serve` that is likely not needed on CI.
    55‚Üí  This will speed up the build time significantly.
    56‚Üí* `--features search` --- Disabling default features means you should then manually enable features that you want, such as the built-in [search] capability.
    57‚Üí* `--vers "^0.4"` --- This will install the most recent version of the `0.4` series.
    58‚Üí  However, versions after like `0.5.0` won't be installed, as they may break your build.
    59‚Üí  Cargo will automatically upgrade mdBook if you have an older version already installed.
    60‚Üí* `--locked` --- This will use the dependencies that were used when mdBook was released.
    61‚Üí  Without `--locked`, it will use the latest version of all dependencies, which may include some fixes since the last release, but may also (rarely) cause build problems.
    62‚Üí
    63‚ÜíYou will likely want to investigate caching options, as building mdBook can be somewhat slow.
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí[search]: guide/reading.md#search
    66‚Üí
    67‚Üí## Running tests
    68‚Üí
    69‚ÜíYou may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70‚ÜíThis can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    71‚Üí
    72‚ÜíThis will require having Rust installed.
    73‚ÜíSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    74‚Üí
    75‚ÜíOther than making sure the appropriate version of Rust is installed, there's not much more than just running `mdbook test` from the book directory.
    76‚Üí
    77‚ÜíYou may also want to consider running other kinds of tests, like [mdbook-linkcheck] which will check for broken links.
    78‚ÜíOr if you have your own style checks, spell checker, or any other tests it might be good to run them in CI.
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí[`mdbook test`]: cli/test.md
    81‚Üí[mdbook-linkcheck]: https://github.com/Michael-F-Bryan/mdbook-linkcheck#continuous-integration
    82‚Üí
    83‚Üí## Deploying
    84‚Üí
    85‚ÜíYou may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86‚ÜíSome may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
    87‚Üí
    88‚ÜíYou'll also need to understand the specifics on how to push a change to your web service.
    89‚ÜíFor example, [GitHub Pages] just requires committing the output onto a specific git branch.
    90‚ÜíOther services may require using something like SSH to connect to a remote server.
    91‚Üí
    92‚ÜíThe basic outline is that you need to run `mdbook build` to generate the output, and then transfer the files (which are in the `book` directory) to the correct location.
    93‚Üí
    94‚ÜíYou may then want to consider if you need to invalidate any caches on your web service.
    95‚Üí
    96‚ÜíSee the [Automated Deployment] wiki page for examples of various different services.
    97‚Üí
    98‚Üí[GitHub Pages]: https://docs.github.com/en/pages
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üí### 404 handling
   101‚Üí
   102‚ÜímdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103‚ÜíThe default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104‚ÜíSome services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
   105‚ÜíFor other services, you may want to consider configuring the web server to use this page as it will provide the reader navigation to get back to the book.
   106‚Üí
   107‚ÜíIf your book is not deployed at the root of the domain, then you should set the [`output.html.site-url`] setting so that the 404 page works correctly.
   108‚ÜíIt needs to know where the book is deployed in order to load the static files (like CSS) correctly.
   109‚ÜíFor example, this guide is deployed at <https://rust-lang.github.io/mdBook/>, and the `site-url` setting is configured like this:
   110‚Üí
   111‚Üí```toml
   112‚Üí# book.toml
   113‚Üí[output.html]
   114‚Üísite-url = "/mdBook/"
   115‚Üí```
   116‚Üí
   117‚ÜíYou can customize the look of the 404 page by creating a file named `src/404.md` in your book.
   118‚ÜíIf you want to use a different filename, you can set [`output.html.input-404`] to a different filename.
   119‚Üí
   120‚Üí[`output.html.site-url`]: format/configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   121‚Üí[`output.html.input-404`]: format/configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
for_developers/README.md
     1‚Üí# For developers
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíWhile `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4‚Üíunderlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5‚Üíflexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6‚Üíconsumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7‚Üíthe book or render it in a different format.
     8‚Üí
     9‚ÜíThe *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10‚Üí`mdbook`.
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíThe two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15‚Üí- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí## The build process
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíThe process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí1. Load the book
    22‚Üí    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23‚Üí       exist
    24‚Üí    - Load the book chapters into memory
    25‚Üí    - Discover which preprocessors/backends should be used
    26‚Üí2. For each backend:
    27‚Üí   1. Run all the preprocessors.
    28‚Üí   2. Call the backend to render the processed result.
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí## Using `mdbook` as a library
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíThe `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33‚Üíexposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34‚Üíprogrammatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35‚ÜíThis can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíThe easiest way to find out how to use the `mdbook-driver` crate is by looking at the
    38‚Üí[API Docs]. The top level documentation explains how one would use the
    39‚Üí[`MDBook`] type to load and build a book, while the [config] module gives a good
    40‚Üíexplanation on the configuration system.
    41‚Üí
    42‚Üí[`MDBook`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/struct.MDBook.html
    43‚Üí[API Docs]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/
    44‚Üí[config]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/config/index.html
for_developers/backends.md
     1‚Üí# Alternative backends
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíA "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4‚Üírendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5‚Üíconfiguration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6‚Üíinformation it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7‚Üí
     8‚ÜíSee [Configuring Renderers](../format/configuration/renderers.md) for more information about using backends.
     9‚Üí
    10‚ÜíThe community has developed several backends.
    11‚ÜíSee the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí## Setting up
    14‚Üí
    15‚ÜíThis page will step you through creating your own alternative backend in the form
    16‚Üíof a simple word counting program. Although it will be written in Rust, there's
    17‚Üíno reason why it couldn't be accomplished using something like Python or Ruby.
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíFirst you'll want to create a new binary program and add `mdbook-renderer` as a
    20‚Üídependency.
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí```shell
    23‚Üí$ cargo new --bin mdbook-wordcount
    24‚Üí$ cd mdbook-wordcount
    25‚Üí$ cargo add mdbook-renderer
    26‚Üí```
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíWhen our `mdbook-wordcount` plugin is invoked, `mdbook` will send it a JSON
    29‚Üíversion of [`RenderContext`] via our plugin's `stdin`. For convenience, there's
    30‚Üía [`RenderContext::from_json()`] constructor which will load a `RenderContext`.
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíThis is all the boilerplate necessary for our backend to load the book.
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí```rust
    35‚Üí// src/main.rs
    36‚Üíuse std::io;
    37‚Üíuse mdbook_renderer::RenderContext;
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üífn main() {
    40‚Üí    let mut stdin = io::stdin();
    41‚Üí    let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
    42‚Üí}
    43‚Üí```
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí> **Note:** The `RenderContext` contains a `version` field. This lets backends
    46‚Üí> figure out whether they are compatible with the version of `mdbook` it's being
    47‚Üí> called by. This `version` comes directly from the corresponding field in
    48‚Üí> `mdbook`'s `Cargo.toml`.
    49‚Üí>
    50‚Üí> It is recommended that backends use the [`semver`] crate to inspect this field
    51‚Üí> and emit a warning if there may be a compatibility issue.
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üí## Inspecting the book
    54‚Üí
    55‚ÜíNow our backend has a copy of the book, lets count how many words are in each
    56‚Üíchapter!
    57‚Üí
    58‚ÜíBecause the `RenderContext` contains a [`Book`] field (`book`), and a `Book` has
    59‚Üíthe [`Book::iter()`] method for iterating over all items in a `Book`, this step
    60‚Üíturns out to be just as easy as the first.
    61‚Üí
    62‚Üí```rust
    63‚Üí
    64‚Üífn main() {
    65‚Üí    let mut stdin = io::stdin();
    66‚Üí    let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí    for item in ctx.book.iter() {
    69‚Üí        if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
    70‚Üí            let num_words = count_words(ch);
    71‚Üí            println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
    72‚Üí        }
    73‚Üí    }
    74‚Üí}
    75‚Üí
    76‚Üífn count_words(ch: &Chapter) -> usize {
    77‚Üí    ch.content.split_whitespace().count()
    78‚Üí}
    79‚Üí```
    80‚Üí
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí## Enabling the backend
    83‚Üí
    84‚ÜíNow we've got the basics running, we want to actually use it. First, install the
    85‚Üíprogram.
    86‚Üí
    87‚Üí```shell
    88‚Üí$ cargo install --path .
    89‚Üí```
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíThen `cd` to the particular book you'd like to count the words of and update its
    92‚Üí`book.toml` file.
    93‚Üí
    94‚Üí```diff
    95‚Üí  [book]
    96‚Üí  title = "mdBook Documentation"
    97‚Üí  description = "Create book from markdown files. Like Gitbook but implemented in Rust"
    98‚Üí  authors = ["Mathieu David", "Michael-F-Bryan"]
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üí+ [output.html]
   101‚Üí
   102‚Üí+ [output.wordcount]
   103‚Üí```
   104‚Üí
   105‚ÜíWhen it loads a book into memory, `mdbook` will inspect your `book.toml` file to
   106‚Üítry and figure out which backends to use by looking for all `output.*` tables.
   107‚ÜíIf none are provided it'll fall back to using the default HTML renderer.
   108‚Üí
   109‚ÜíNotably, this means if you want to add your own custom backend you'll also need
   110‚Üíto make sure to add the HTML backend, even if its table just stays empty.
   111‚Üí
   112‚ÜíNow you just need to build your book like normal, and everything should *Just
   113‚ÜíWork*.
   114‚Üí
   115‚Üí```shell
   116‚Üí$ mdbook build
   117‚Üí...
   118‚Üí2018-01-16 07:31:15 [INFO] (mdbook::renderer): Invoking the "mdbook-wordcount" renderer
   119‚ÜímdBook: 126
   120‚ÜíCommand Line Tool: 224
   121‚Üíinit: 283
   122‚Üíbuild: 145
   123‚Üíwatch: 146
   124‚Üíserve: 292
   125‚Üítest: 139
   126‚ÜíFormat: 30
   127‚ÜíSUMMARY.md: 259
   128‚ÜíConfiguration: 784
   129‚ÜíTheme: 304
   130‚Üíindex.hbs: 447
   131‚ÜíSyntax highlighting: 314
   132‚ÜíMathJax Support: 153
   133‚ÜíRust code specific features: 148
   134‚ÜíFor Developers: 788
   135‚ÜíAlternative Backends: 710
   136‚ÜíContributors: 85
   137‚Üí```
   138‚Üí
   139‚ÜíThe reason we didn't need to specify the full name/path of our `wordcount`
   140‚Üíbackend is because `mdbook` will try to *infer* the program's name via
   141‚Üíconvention. The executable for the `foo` backend is typically called
   142‚Üí`mdbook-foo`, with an associated `[output.foo]` entry in the `book.toml`. To
   143‚Üíexplicitly tell `mdbook` what command to invoke (it may require command-line
   144‚Üíarguments or be an interpreted script), you can use the `command` field.
   145‚Üí
   146‚Üí```diff
   147‚Üí  [book]
   148‚Üí  title = "mdBook Documentation"
   149‚Üí  description = "Create book from markdown files. Like Gitbook but implemented in Rust"
   150‚Üí  authors = ["Mathieu David", "Michael-F-Bryan"]
   151‚Üí
   152‚Üí  [output.html]
   153‚Üí
   154‚Üí  [output.wordcount]
   155‚Üí+ command = "python /path/to/wordcount.py"
   156‚Üí```
   157‚Üí
   158‚Üí
   159‚Üí## Configuration
   160‚Üí
   161‚ÜíNow imagine you don't want to count the number of words on a particular chapter
   162‚Üí(it might be generated text/code, etc). The canonical way to do this is via the
   163‚Üíusual `book.toml` configuration file by adding items to your `[output.foo]`
   164‚Üítable.
   165‚Üí
   166‚ÜíThe `Config` can be treated roughly as a nested hashmap which lets you call
   167‚Üímethods like `get()` to access the config's contents, with a
   168‚Üí`get_deserialized()` convenience method for retrieving a value and automatically
   169‚Üídeserializing to some arbitrary type `T`.
   170‚Üí
   171‚ÜíTo implement this, we'll create our own serializable `WordcountConfig` struct
   172‚Üíwhich will encapsulate all configuration for this backend.
   173‚Üí
   174‚ÜíFirst add `serde` and `serde_derive` to your `Cargo.toml`,
   175‚Üí
   176‚Üí```
   177‚Üí$ cargo add serde serde_derive
   178‚Üí```
   179‚Üí
   180‚ÜíAnd then you can create the config struct,
   181‚Üí
   182‚Üí```rust
   183‚Üíuse serde_derive::{Serialize, Deserialize};
   184‚Üí
   185‚Üí...
   186‚Üí
   187‚Üí#[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   188‚Üí#[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
   189‚Üípub struct WordcountConfig {
   190‚Üí  pub ignores: Vec<String>,
   191‚Üí}
   192‚Üí```
   193‚Üí
   194‚ÜíNow we just need to deserialize the `WordcountConfig` from our `RenderContext`
   195‚Üíand then add a check to make sure we skip ignored chapters.
   196‚Üí
   197‚Üí```diff
   198‚Üí  fn main() {
   199‚Üí      let mut stdin = io::stdin();
   200‚Üí      let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
   201‚Üí+     let cfg: WordcountConfig = ctx.config
   202‚Üí+         .get_deserialized("output.wordcount")
   203‚Üí+         .unwrap_or_default();
   204‚Üí
   205‚Üí      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   206‚Üí          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   207‚Üí+             if cfg.ignores.contains(&ch.name) {
   208‚Üí+                 continue;
   209‚Üí+             }
   210‚Üí+
   211‚Üí              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   212‚Üí              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   213‚Üí          }
   214‚Üí      }
   215‚Üí  }
   216‚Üí```
   217‚Üí
   218‚Üí
   219‚Üí## Output and signalling failure
   220‚Üí
   221‚ÜíWhile it's nice to print word counts to the terminal when a book is built, it
   222‚Üímight also be a good idea to output them to a file somewhere. `mdbook` tells a
   223‚Üíbackend where it should place any generated output via the `destination` field
   224‚Üíin [`RenderContext`].
   225‚Üí
   226‚Üí```diff
   227‚Üí+ use std::fs::{self, File};
   228‚Üí+ use std::io::{self, Write};
   229‚Üí- use std::io;
   230‚Üí  use mdbook::renderer::RenderContext;
   231‚Üí  use mdbook::book::{BookItem, Chapter};
   232‚Üí
   233‚Üí  fn main() {
   234‚Üí    ...
   235‚Üí
   236‚Üí+     let _ = fs::create_dir_all(&ctx.destination);
   237‚Üí+     let mut f = File::create(ctx.destination.join("wordcounts.txt")).unwrap();
   238‚Üí+
   239‚Üí      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   240‚Üí          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   241‚Üí              ...
   242‚Üí
   243‚Üí              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   244‚Üí              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   245‚Üí+             writeln!(f, "{}: {}", ch.name, num_words).unwrap();
   246‚Üí          }
   247‚Üí      }
   248‚Üí  }
   249‚Üí```
   250‚Üí
   251‚Üí> **Note:** There is no guarantee that the destination directory exists or is
   252‚Üí> empty (`mdbook` may leave the previous contents to let backends do caching),
   253‚Üí> so it's always a good idea to create it with `fs::create_dir_all()`.
   254‚Üí>
   255‚Üí> If the destination directory already exists, don't assume it will be empty.
   256‚Üí> To allow backends to cache the results from previous runs, `mdbook` may leave
   257‚Üí> old content in the directory.
   258‚Üí
   259‚ÜíThere's always the possibility that an error will occur while processing a book
   260‚Üí(just look at all the `unwrap()`'s we've written already), so `mdbook` will
   261‚Üíinterpret a non-zero exit code as a rendering failure.
   262‚Üí
   263‚ÜíFor example, if we wanted to make sure all chapters have an *even* number of
   264‚Üíwords, erroring out if an odd number is encountered, then you may do something
   265‚Üílike this:
   266‚Üí
   267‚Üí```diff
   268‚Üí+ use std::process;
   269‚Üí  ...
   270‚Üí
   271‚Üí  fn main() {
   272‚Üí      ...
   273‚Üí
   274‚Üí      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   275‚Üí          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   276‚Üí              ...
   277‚Üí
   278‚Üí              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   279‚Üí              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   280‚Üí              writeln!(f, "{}: {}", ch.name, num_words).unwrap();
   281‚Üí
   282‚Üí+             if cfg.deny_odds && num_words % 2 == 1 {
   283‚Üí+               eprintln!("{} has an odd number of words!", ch.name);
   284‚Üí+               process::exit(1);
   285‚Üí+             }
   286‚Üí          }
   287‚Üí      }
   288‚Üí  }
   289‚Üí
   290‚Üí  #[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   291‚Üí  #[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
   292‚Üí  pub struct WordcountConfig {
   293‚Üí      pub ignores: Vec<String>,
   294‚Üí+     pub deny_odds: bool,
   295‚Üí  }
   296‚Üí```
   297‚Üí
   298‚ÜíNow, if we reinstall the backend and build a book,
   299‚Üí
   300‚Üí```shell
   301‚Üí$ cargo install --path . --force
   302‚Üí$ mdbook build /path/to/book
   303‚Üí...
   304‚Üí2018-01-16 21:21:39 [INFO] (mdbook::renderer): Invoking the "wordcount" renderer
   305‚ÜímdBook: 126
   306‚ÜíCommand Line Tool: 224
   307‚Üíinit: 283
   308‚Üíinit has an odd number of words!
   309‚Üí2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::renderer): Renderer exited with non-zero return code.
   310‚Üí2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::utils): Error: Rendering failed
   311‚Üí2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::utils):    Caused By: The "mdbook-wordcount" renderer failed
   312‚Üí```
   313‚Üí
   314‚ÜíAs you've probably already noticed, output from the plugin's subprocess is
   315‚Üíimmediately passed through to the user. It is encouraged for plugins to follow
   316‚Üíthe "rule of silence" and only generate output when necessary (e.g. an error in
   317‚Üígeneration or a warning).
   318‚Üí
   319‚ÜíAll environment variables are passed through to the backend, allowing you to use
   320‚Üíthe usual `MDBOOK_LOG` to control logging verbosity.
   321‚Üí
   322‚Üí## Wrapping up
   323‚Üí
   324‚ÜíAlthough contrived, hopefully this example was enough to show how you'd create
   325‚Üían alternative backend for `mdbook`. If you feel it's missing something, don't
   326‚Üíhesitate to create an issue in the [issue tracker] so we can improve the user
   327‚Üíguide.
   328‚Üí
   329‚ÜíThe existing backends mentioned towards the start of this chapter should serve
   330‚Üías a good example of how it's done in real life, so feel free to skim through
   331‚Üíthe source code or ask questions.
   332‚Üí
   333‚Üí
   334‚Üí[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
   335‚Üí[`RenderContext`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/struct.RenderContext.html
   336‚Üí[`RenderContext::from_json()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/struct.RenderContext.html#method.from_json
   337‚Üí[`semver`]: https://crates.io/crates/semver
   338‚Üí[`Book`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/book/struct.Book.html
   339‚Üí[`Book::iter()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/book/struct.Book.html#method.iter
   340‚Üí[`Config`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/config/struct.Config.html
   341‚Üí[issue tracker]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues
for_developers/mdbook-wordcount/src/main.rs
    12‚Üífn main() {
    40‚Üífn count_words(ch: &Chapter) -> usize {
    44‚Üí#[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
    45‚Üí#[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
    46‚Üípub struct WordcountConfig {
    47‚Üí    pub ignores: Vec<String>,
    48‚Üí    pub deny_odds: bool,
    49‚Üí}
for_developers/preprocessors.md
     1‚Üí# Preprocessors
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíA *preprocessor* is simply a bit of code which gets run immediately after the
     4‚Üíbook is loaded and before it gets rendered, allowing you to update and mutate
     5‚Üíthe book. Possible use cases are:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí- Creating custom helpers like `\{{#include /path/to/file.md}}`
     8‚Üí- Substituting in latex-style expressions (`$$ \frac{1}{3} $$`) with their
     9‚Üí  mathjax equivalents
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíSee [Configuring Preprocessors](../format/configuration/preprocessors.md) for more information about using preprocessors.
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí## Hooking into MDBook
    14‚Üí
    15‚ÜíMDBook uses a fairly simple mechanism for discovering third party plugins.
    16‚ÜíA new table is added to `book.toml` (e.g. `[preprocessor.foo]` for the `foo`
    17‚Üípreprocessor) and then `mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` program as
    18‚Üípart of the build process.
    19‚Üí
    20‚ÜíOnce the preprocessor has been defined and the build process starts, mdBook executes the command defined in the `preprocessor.foo.command` key twice.
    21‚ÜíThe first time it runs the preprocessor to determine if it supports the given renderer.
    22‚ÜímdBook passes two arguments to the process: the first argument is the string `supports` and the second argument is the renderer name.
    23‚ÜíThe preprocessor should exit with a status code 0 if it supports the given renderer, or return a non-zero exit code if it does not.
    24‚Üí
    25‚ÜíIf the preprocessor supports the renderer, then mdbook runs it a second time, passing JSON data into stdin.
    26‚ÜíThe JSON consists of an array of `[context, book]` where `context` is the serialized object [`PreprocessorContext`] and `book` is a [`Book`] object containing the content of the book.
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíThe preprocessor should return the JSON format of the [`Book`] object to stdout, with any modifications it wishes to perform.
    29‚Üí
    30‚ÜíThe easiest way to get started is by creating your own implementation of the
    31‚Üí`Preprocessor` trait (e.g. in `lib.rs`) and then creating a shell binary which
    32‚Üítranslates inputs to the correct `Preprocessor` method. For convenience, there
    33‚Üíis [an example no-op preprocessor] in the `examples/` directory which can easily
    34‚Üíbe adapted for other preprocessors.
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí<details>
    37‚Üí<summary>Example no-op preprocessor</summary>
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí```rust
    40‚Üí// nop-preprocessors.rs
    41‚Üí
    42‚Üí{{#include ../../../examples/nop-preprocessor.rs}}
    43‚Üí```
    44‚Üí</details>
    45‚Üí
    46‚Üí## Hints for implementing a preprocessor
    47‚Üí
    48‚ÜíBy pulling in `mdbook-preprocessor` as a library, preprocessors can have access to the
    49‚Üíexisting infrastructure for dealing with books.
    50‚Üí
    51‚ÜíFor example, a custom preprocessor could use the
    52‚Üí[`parse_input()`] function to deserialize the JSON written to
    53‚Üí`stdin`. Then each chapter of the `Book` can be mutated in-place via
    54‚Üí[`Book::for_each_mut()`], and then written to `stdout` with the `serde_json`
    55‚Üícrate.
    56‚Üí
    57‚ÜíChapters can be accessed either directly (by recursively iterating over
    58‚Üíchapters) or via the `Book::for_each_mut()` convenience method.
    59‚Üí
    60‚ÜíThe `chapter.content` is just a string which happens to be markdown. While it's
    61‚Üíentirely possible to use regular expressions or do a manual find & replace,
    62‚Üíyou'll probably want to process the input into something more computer-friendly.
    63‚ÜíThe [`mdbook-markdown`] crate exposes the [`pulldown-cmark`][pc] crate used by mdBook to parse Markdown. The [`pulldown-cmark-to-cmark`][pctc] crate can be used to translate events back into markdown text.
    64‚Üí
    65‚ÜíThe following code block shows how to remove all emphasis from markdown,
    66‚Üíwithout accidentally breaking the document.
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí```rust
    69‚Üí{{#rustdoc_include ../../../examples/remove-emphasis/mdbook-remove-emphasis/src/main.rs:remove_emphasis}}
    70‚Üí```
    71‚Üí
    72‚ÜíTake a look at the [full example source][emphasis-example] for more details.
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí## Implementing a preprocessor with a different language
    75‚Üí
    76‚ÜíThe fact that mdBook utilizes stdin and stdout to communicate with the preprocessors makes it easy to implement them in a language other than Rust.
    77‚ÜíThe following code shows how to implement a simple preprocessor in Python, which will modify the content of the first chapter.
    78‚ÜíThe example below follows the configuration shown above with `preprocessor.foo.command` actually pointing to a Python script.
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí```python
    81‚Üíimport json
    82‚Üíimport sys
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üíif __name__ == '__main__':
    86‚Üí    if len(sys.argv) > 1: # we check if we received any argument
    87‚Üí        if sys.argv[1] == "supports": 
    88‚Üí            # then we are good to return an exit status code of 0, since the other argument will just be the renderer's name
    89‚Üí            sys.exit(0)
    90‚Üí
    91‚Üí    # load both the context and the book representations from stdin
    92‚Üí    context, book = json.load(sys.stdin)
    93‚Üí    # and now, we can just modify the content of the first chapter
    94‚Üí    book['items'][0]['Chapter']['content'] = '# Hello'
    95‚Üí    # we are done with the book's modification, we can just print it to stdout, 
    96‚Üí    print(json.dumps(book))
    97‚Üí```
    98‚Üí
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üí[emphasis-example]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/tree/master/examples/remove-emphasis/
   101‚Üí[pc]: https://crates.io/crates/pulldown-cmark
   102‚Üí[pctc]: https://crates.io/crates/pulldown-cmark-to-cmark
   103‚Üí[an example no-op preprocessor]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/blob/master/examples/nop-preprocessor.rs
   104‚Üí[`parse_input()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/fn.parse_input.html
   105‚Üí[`Book::for_each_mut()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/book/struct.Book.html#method.for_each_mut
   106‚Üí[`PreprocessorContext`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/struct.PreprocessorContext.html
   107‚Üí[`Book`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/book/struct.Book.html
   108‚Üí[`mdbook-markdown`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-markdown/latest/mdbook_markdown/
format/README.md
     1‚Üí# Format
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíIn this section you will learn how to:
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí- Structure your book correctly
     6‚Üí- Format your `SUMMARY.md` file
     7‚Üí- Configure your book using `book.toml`
     8‚Üí- Customize your theme
format/configuration/README.md
     1‚Üí# Configuration
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThis section details the configuration options available in the ***book.toml***:
     4‚Üí- **[General]** configuration including the `book`, `rust`, `build` sections
     5‚Üí- **[Preprocessor]** configuration for default and custom book preprocessors
     6‚Üí- **[Renderer]** configuration for the HTML, Markdown and custom renderers
     7‚Üí- **[Environment Variable]** configuration for overriding configuration options in your environment
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí[General]: general.md
    10‚Üí[Preprocessor]: preprocessors.md
    11‚Üí[Renderer]: renderers.md
    12‚Üí[Environment Variable]: environment-variables.md
format/configuration/environment-variables.md
     1‚Üí# Environment variables
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíAll configuration values can be overridden from the command line by setting the
     4‚Üícorresponding environment variable. Because many operating systems restrict
     5‚Üíenvironment variables to be alphanumeric characters or `_`, the configuration
     6‚Üíkey needs to be formatted slightly differently to the normal `foo.bar.baz` form.
     7‚Üí
     8‚ÜíVariables starting with `MDBOOK_` are used for configuration. The key is created
     9‚Üíby removing the `MDBOOK_` prefix and turning the resulting string into
    10‚Üí`kebab-case`. Double underscores (`__`) separate nested keys, while a single
    11‚Üíunderscore (`_`) is replaced with a dash (`-`).
    12‚Üí
    13‚ÜíFor example:
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí- `MDBOOK_book` -> `book`
    16‚Üí- `MDBOOK_BOOK` -> `book`
    17‚Üí- `MDBOOK_BOOK__TITLE` -> `book.title`
    18‚Üí- `MDBOOK_BOOK__TEXT_DIRECTION` -> `book.text-direction`
    19‚Üí
    20‚ÜíSo by setting the `MDBOOK_BOOK__TITLE` environment variable you can override the
    21‚Üíbook's title without needing to touch your `book.toml`.
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí> **Note:** To facilitate setting more complex config items, the value of an
    24‚Üí> environment variable is first parsed as JSON, falling back to a string if the
    25‚Üí> parse fails.
    26‚Üí>
    27‚Üí> This means, if you so desired, you could override all book metadata when
    28‚Üí> building the book with something like
    29‚Üí>
    30‚Üí> ```shell
    31‚Üí> $ export MDBOOK_BOOK='{"title": "My Awesome Book", "authors": ["Michael-F-Bryan"]}'
    32‚Üí> $ mdbook build
    33‚Üí> ```
    34‚Üí
    35‚ÜíThe latter case may be useful in situations where `mdbook` is invoked from a
    36‚Üíscript or CI, where it sometimes isn't possible to update the `book.toml` before
    37‚Üíbuilding.
format/configuration/general.md
     1‚Üí# General configuration
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíYou can configure the parameters for your book in the ***book.toml*** file.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíHere is an example of what a ***book.toml*** file might look like:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```toml
     8‚Üí[book]
     9‚Üítitle = "Example book"
    10‚Üíauthors = ["John Doe"]
    11‚Üídescription = "The example book covers examples."
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí[rust]
    14‚Üíedition = "2018"
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üí[build]
    17‚Üíbuild-dir = "my-example-book"
    18‚Üícreate-missing = false
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí[preprocessor.index]
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí[preprocessor.links]
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üí[output.html]
    25‚Üíadditional-css = ["custom.css"]
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí[output.html.search]
    28‚Üílimit-results = 15
    29‚Üí```
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí## Supported configuration options
    32‚Üí
    33‚ÜíIt is important to note that **any** relative path specified in the
    34‚Üíconfiguration will always be taken relative from the root of the book where the
    35‚Üíconfiguration file is located.
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí### General metadata
    38‚Üí
    39‚ÜíThis is general information about your book.
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí- **title:** The title of the book
    42‚Üí- **authors:** The author(s) of the book
    43‚Üí- **description:** A description for the book, which is added as meta
    44‚Üí  information in the html `<head>` of each page
    45‚Üí- **src:** By default, the source directory is found in the directory named
    46‚Üí  `src` directly under the root folder. But this is configurable with the `src`
    47‚Üí  key in the configuration file.
    48‚Üí- **language:** The main language of the book, which is used as a language attribute `<html lang="en">` for example.
    49‚Üí  This is also used to derive the direction of text (RTL, LTR) within the book.
    50‚Üí- **text-direction**: The direction of text in the book: Left-to-right (LTR) or Right-to-left (RTL). Possible values: `ltr`, `rtl`.
    51‚Üí  When not specified, the text direction is derived from the book's `language` attribute.
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üí**book.toml**
    54‚Üí```toml
    55‚Üí[book]
    56‚Üítitle = "Example book"
    57‚Üíauthors = ["John Doe", "Jane Doe"]
    58‚Üídescription = "The example book covers examples."
    59‚Üísrc = "my-src"  # the source files will be found in `root/my-src` instead of `root/src`
    60‚Üílanguage = "en"
    61‚Üítext-direction = "ltr"
    62‚Üí```
    63‚Üí
    64‚Üí### Rust options
    65‚Üí
    66‚ÜíOptions for the Rust language, relevant to running tests and playground
    67‚Üíintegration.
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üí```toml
    70‚Üí[rust]
    71‚Üíedition = "2015"   # the default edition for code blocks
    72‚Üí```
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí- **edition**: Rust edition to use by default for the code snippets. Default
    75‚Üí  is `"2015"`. Individual code blocks can be controlled with the `edition2015`,
    76‚Üí  `edition2018`, `edition2021` or `edition2024` annotations, such as:
    77‚Üí
    78‚Üí  ~~~text
    79‚Üí  ```rust,edition2015
    80‚Üí  // This only works in 2015.
    81‚Üí  let try = true;
    82‚Üí  ```
    83‚Üí  ~~~
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí### Build options
    86‚Üí
    87‚ÜíThis controls the build process of your book.
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí```toml
    90‚Üí[build]
    91‚Üíbuild-dir = "book"                # the directory where the output is placed
    92‚Üícreate-missing = true             # whether or not to create missing pages
    93‚Üíuse-default-preprocessors = true  # use the default preprocessors
    94‚Üíextra-watch-dirs = []             # directories to watch for triggering builds
    95‚Üí```
    96‚Üí
    97‚Üí- **build-dir:** The directory to put the rendered book in. By default this is
    98‚Üí  `book/` in the book's root directory.
    99‚Üí  This can overridden with the `--dest-dir` CLI option.
   100‚Üí- **create-missing:** By default, any missing files specified in `SUMMARY.md`
   101‚Üí  will be created when the book is built (i.e. `create-missing = true`). If this
   102‚Üí  is `false` then the build process will instead exit with an error if any files
   103‚Üí  do not exist.
   104‚Üí- **use-default-preprocessors:** Disable the default preprocessors (of `links` &
   105‚Üí  `index`) by setting this option to `false`.
   106‚Üí
   107‚Üí  If you have the same, and/or other preprocessors declared via their table
   108‚Üí  of configuration, they will run instead.
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üí  - For clarity, with no preprocessor configuration, the default `links` and
   111‚Üí    `index` will run.
   112‚Üí  - Setting `use-default-preprocessors = false` will disable these
   113‚Üí    default preprocessors from running.
   114‚Üí  - Adding `[preprocessor.links]`, for example, will ensure, regardless of
   115‚Üí    `use-default-preprocessors` that `links` it will run.
   116‚Üí- **extra-watch-dirs**: A list of paths to directories that will be watched in
   117‚Üí  the `watch` and `serve` commands. Changes to files under these directories will
   118‚Üí  trigger rebuilds. Useful if your book depends on files outside its `src` directory.
format/configuration/preprocessors.md
     1‚Üí# Configuring Preprocessors
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíPreprocessors are extensions that can modify the raw Markdown source before it gets sent to the renderer.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíThe following preprocessors are built-in and included by default:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí- `links`: Expands the `{{ #playground }}`, `{{ #include }}`, and `{{ #rustdoc_include }}` handlebars
     8‚Üí  helpers in a chapter to include the contents of a file.
     9‚Üí  See [Including files] for more.
    10‚Üí- `index`: Convert all chapter files named `README.md` into `index.md`. That is
    11‚Üí  to say, all `README.md` would be rendered to an index file `index.html` in the
    12‚Üí  rendered book.
    13‚Üí
    14‚ÜíThe built-in preprocessors can be disabled with the [`build.use-default-preprocessors`] config option.
    15‚Üí
    16‚ÜíThe community has developed several preprocessors.
    17‚ÜíSee the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available preprocessors.
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíFor information on how to create a new preprocessor, see the [Preprocessors for Developers] chapter.
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí[Including files]: ../mdbook.md#including-files
    22‚Üí[`build.use-default-preprocessors`]: general.md#build-options
    23‚Üí[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
    24‚Üí[Preprocessors for Developers]: ../../for_developers/preprocessors.md
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí## Custom preprocessor configuration
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíPreprocessors can be added by including a `preprocessor` table in `book.toml` with the name of the preprocessor.
    29‚ÜíFor example, if you have a preprocessor called `mdbook-example`, then you can include it with:
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí```toml
    32‚Üí[preprocessor.example]
    33‚Üí```
    34‚Üí
    35‚ÜíWith this table, mdBook will execute the `mdbook-example` preprocessor.
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíThis table can include additional key-value pairs that are specific to the preprocessor.
    38‚ÜíFor example, if our example preprocessor needed some extra configuration options:
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí```toml
    41‚Üí[preprocessor.example]
    42‚Üísome-extra-feature = true
    43‚Üí```
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí## Locking a preprocessor dependency to a renderer
    46‚Üí
    47‚ÜíYou can explicitly specify that a preprocessor should run for a renderer by
    48‚Üíbinding the two together.
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí```toml
    51‚Üí[preprocessor.example]
    52‚Üírenderers = ["html"]  # example preprocessor only runs with the HTML renderer
    53‚Üí```
    54‚Üí
    55‚Üí## Provide your own command
    56‚Üí
    57‚ÜíBy default when you add a `[preprocessor.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    58‚Üí`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable. If you want to use a
    59‚Üídifferent program name or pass in command-line arguments, this behaviour can
    60‚Üíbe overridden by adding a `command` field.
    61‚Üí
    62‚Üí```toml
    63‚Üí[preprocessor.random]
    64‚Üícommand = "python random.py"
    65‚Üí```
    66‚Üí
    67‚Üí### Optional preprocessors
    68‚Üí
    69‚ÜíIf you enable a preprocessor that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    70‚ÜíThis behavior can be changed by marking the preprocessor as optional:
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí```toml
    73‚Üí[preprocessor.example]
    74‚Üíoptional = true
    75‚Üí```
    76‚Üí
    77‚ÜíThis demotes the error to a warning.
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí## Require a certain order
    80‚Üí
    81‚ÜíThe order in which preprocessors are run can be controlled with the `before` and `after` fields.
    82‚ÜíFor example, suppose you want your `linenos` preprocessor to process lines that may have been `{{#include}}`d; then you want it to run after the built-in `links` preprocessor, which you can require using either the `before` or `after` field:
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üí```toml
    85‚Üí[preprocessor.linenos]
    86‚Üíafter = [ "links" ]
    87‚Üí```
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üíor
    90‚Üí
    91‚Üí```toml
    92‚Üí[preprocessor.links]
    93‚Üíbefore = [ "linenos" ]
    94‚Üí```
    95‚Üí
    96‚ÜíIt would also be possible, though redundant, to specify both of the above in the same config file.
    97‚Üí
    98‚ÜíPreprocessors having the same priority specified through `before` and `after` are sorted by name.
    99‚ÜíAny infinite loops will be detected and produce an error.
format/configuration/renderers.md
     1‚Üí# Configuring Renderers
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíRenderers (also called "backends") are responsible for creating the output of the book.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíThe following backends are built-in:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí* [`html`](#html-renderer-options) --- This renders the book to HTML.
     8‚Üí  This is enabled by default if no other `[output]` tables are defined in `book.toml`.
     9‚Üí* [`markdown`](#markdown-renderer) --- This outputs the book as markdown after running the preprocessors.
    10‚Üí  This is useful for debugging preprocessors.
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíThe community has developed several backends.
    13‚ÜíSee the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    14‚Üí
    15‚ÜíFor information on how to create a new backend, see the [Backends for Developers] chapter.
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
    18‚Üí[Backends for Developers]: ../../for_developers/backends.md
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí## Output tables
    21‚Üí
    22‚ÜíBackends can be added by including a `output` table in `book.toml` with the name of the backend.
    23‚ÜíFor example, if you have a backend called `mdbook-wordcount`, then you can include it with:
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí```toml
    26‚Üí[output.wordcount]
    27‚Üí```
    28‚Üí
    29‚ÜíWith this table, mdBook will execute the `mdbook-wordcount` backend.
    30‚Üí
    31‚ÜíThis table can include additional key-value pairs that are specific to the backend.
    32‚ÜíFor example, if our example backend needed some extra configuration options:
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí```toml
    35‚Üí[output.wordcount]
    36‚Üíignores = ["Example Chapter"]
    37‚Üí```
    38‚Üí
    39‚ÜíIf you define any `[output]` tables, then the `html` backend is not enabled by default.
    40‚ÜíIf you want to keep the `html` backend running, then just include it in the `book.toml` file.
    41‚ÜíFor example:
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí```toml
    44‚Üí[book]
    45‚Üítitle = "My Awesome Book"
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí[output.wordcount]
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üí[output.html]
    50‚Üí```
    51‚Üí
    52‚ÜíIf more than one `output` table is included, this changes the behavior for the layout of the output directory.
    53‚ÜíIf there is only one backend, then it places its output directly in the `book` directory (see [`build.build-dir`] to override this location).
    54‚ÜíIf there is more than one backend, then each backend is placed in a separate directory underneath `book`.
    55‚ÜíFor example, the above would have directories `book/html` and `book/wordcount`.
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí[`build.build-dir`]: general.md#build-options
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üí### Custom backend commands
    60‚Üí
    61‚ÜíBy default when you add an `[output.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    62‚Üí`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable.
    63‚ÜíIf you want to use a different program name or pass in command-line arguments,
    64‚Üíthis behaviour can be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    65‚Üí
    66‚Üí```toml
    67‚Üí[output.random]
    68‚Üícommand = "python random.py"
    69‚Üí```
    70‚Üí
    71‚Üí### Optional backends
    72‚Üí
    73‚ÜíIf you enable a backend that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    74‚ÜíThis behavior can be changed by marking the backend as optional:
    75‚Üí
    76‚Üí```toml
    77‚Üí[output.wordcount]
    78‚Üíoptional = true
    79‚Üí```
    80‚Üí
    81‚ÜíThis demotes the error to a warning.
    82‚Üí
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üí## HTML renderer options
    85‚Üí
    86‚ÜíThe HTML renderer has a variety of options detailed below.
    87‚ÜíThey should be specified in the `[output.html]` table of the `book.toml` file.
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí```toml
    90‚Üí# Example book.toml file with all output options.
    91‚Üí[book]
    92‚Üítitle = "Example book"
    93‚Üíauthors = ["John Doe", "Jane Doe"]
    94‚Üídescription = "The example book covers examples."
    95‚Üí
    96‚Üí[output.html]
    97‚Üítheme = "my-theme"
    98‚Üídefault-theme = "light"
    99‚Üípreferred-dark-theme = "navy"
   100‚Üísmart-punctuation = true
   101‚Üídefinition-lists = true
   102‚Üíadmonitions = true
   103‚Üímathjax-support = false
   104‚Üíadditional-css = ["custom.css", "custom2.css"]
   105‚Üíadditional-js = ["custom.js"]
   106‚Üíno-section-label = false
   107‚Üígit-repository-url = "https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook"
   108‚Üígit-repository-icon = "fab-github"
   109‚Üíedit-url-template = "https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/edit/master/guide/{path}"
   110‚Üísite-url = "/example-book/"
   111‚Üícname = "myproject.rs"
   112‚Üíinput-404 = "not-found.md"
   113‚Üísidebar-header-nav = true
   114‚Üí```
   115‚Üí
   116‚ÜíThe following configuration options are available:
   117‚Üí
   118‚Üí- **theme:** mdBook comes with a default theme and all the resource files needed
   119‚Üí  for it. But if this option is set, mdBook will selectively overwrite the theme
   120‚Üí  files with the ones found in the specified folder.
   121‚Üí- **default-theme:** The theme color scheme to select by default in the
   122‚Üí  'Change Theme' dropdown. Defaults to `light`.
   123‚Üí- **preferred-dark-theme:** The default dark theme. This theme will be used if
   124‚Üí  the browser requests the dark version of the site via the
   125‚Üí  [`prefers-color-scheme`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@media/prefers-color-scheme)
   126‚Üí  CSS media query. Defaults to `navy`.
   127‚Üí- **smart-punctuation:** Converts quotes to curly quotes, `...` to `‚Ä¶`, `--` to en-dash, and `---` to em-dash.
   128‚Üí  See [Smart Punctuation](../markdown.md#smart-punctuation).
   129‚Üí  Defaults to `true`.
   130‚Üí- **definition-lists:** Enables [definition lists](../markdown.md#definition-lists). Defaults to `true`.
   131‚Üí- **admonitions:** Enables [admonitions](../markdown.md#admonitions). Defaults to `true`.
   132‚Üí- **mathjax-support:** Adds support for [MathJax](../mathjax.md). Defaults to
   133‚Üí  `false`.
   134‚Üí- **additional-css:** If you need to slightly change the appearance of your book
   135‚Üí  without overwriting the whole style, you can specify a set of stylesheets that
   136‚Üí  will be loaded after the default ones where you can surgically change the
   137‚Üí  style.
   138‚Üí- **additional-js:** If you need to add some behaviour to your book without
   139‚Üí  removing the current behaviour, you can specify a set of JavaScript files that
   140‚Üí  will be loaded alongside the default one.
   141‚Üí- **no-section-label:** mdBook by defaults adds numeric section labels in the table of
   142‚Üí  contents column. For example, "1.", "2.1". Set this option to true to disable
   143‚Üí  those labels. Defaults to `false`.
   144‚Üí- **git-repository-url:**  A url to the git repository for the book. If provided
   145‚Üí  an icon link will be output in the menu bar of the book.
   146‚Üí- **git-repository-icon:** The Font Awesome icon class to use for the git repository link. Defaults to `fab-github` which looks like <i class="fab fa-github"></i>. If you are not using GitHub, another option to consider is `fas-code-fork` which looks like <i class="fas fa-code-fork"></i>. The start of the string should be `fa-` for regular icons, `fas-` for solid icons, or `fab-` for brand icons. See the [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search) for the available icons.
   147‚Üí- **edit-url-template:** Edit url template, when provided shows a
   148‚Üí  "Suggest an edit" button (which looks like <i class="fas fa-pencil"></i>) for directly jumping to editing the currently
   149‚Üí  viewed page. For e.g. GitHub projects set this to
   150‚Üí  `https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/edit/<branch>/{path}` or for
   151‚Üí  Bitbucket projects set it to
   152‚Üí  `https://bitbucket.org/<owner>/<repo>/src/<branch>/{path}?mode=edit`
   153‚Üí  where {path} will be replaced with the full path of the file in the
   154‚Üí  repository.
   155‚Üí- **input-404:** The name of the markdown file used for missing files.
   156‚Üí  The corresponding output file will be the same, with the extension replaced with `html`.
   157‚Üí  Defaults to `404.md`.
   158‚Üí- **site-url:** The url where the book will be hosted. This is required to ensure
   159‚Üí  navigation links and script/css imports in the 404 file work correctly, even when accessing
   160‚Üí  urls in subdirectories. Defaults to `/`. If `site-url` is set,
   161‚Üí  make sure to use document relative links for your assets, meaning they should not start with `/`.
   162‚Üí- **cname:** The DNS subdomain or apex domain at which your book will be hosted.
   163‚Üí  This string will be written to a file named CNAME in the root of your site, as
   164‚Üí  required by GitHub Pages (see [*Managing a custom domain for your GitHub Pages
   165‚Üí  site*][custom domain]).
   166‚Üí- **hash-files:** Include a cryptographic "fingerprint" of the files' contents in static asset filenames,
   167‚Üí  so that if the contents of the file are changed, the name of the file will also change.
   168‚Üí  For example, `css/chrome.css` may become `css/chrome-9b8f428e.css`.
   169‚Üí  Chapter HTML files are not renamed.
   170‚Üí  Static CSS and JS files can reference each other using `{{ resource "filename" }}` directives.
   171‚Üí  Defaults to `true`.
   172‚Üí- **sidebar-header-nav:** If `true`, the sidebar will contain navigation for headers on the current page. Default is `true`.
   173‚Üí
   174‚Üí[custom domain]: https://docs.github.com/en/github/working-with-github-pages/managing-a-custom-domain-for-your-github-pages-site
   175‚Üí
   176‚Üí### `[output.html.print]`
   177‚Üí
   178‚ÜíThe `[output.html.print]` table provides options for controlling the printable output.
   179‚ÜíBy default, mdBook will include an icon on the top right of the book (which looks like <i class="fas fa-print"></i>) that will print the book as a single page.
   180‚Üí
   181‚Üí```toml
   182‚Üí[output.html.print]
   183‚Üíenable = true    # include support for printable output
   184‚Üípage-break = true # insert page-break after each chapter
   185‚Üí```
   186‚Üí
   187‚Üí- **enable:** Enable print support. When `false`, all print support will not be
   188‚Üí  rendered. Defaults to `true`.
   189‚Üí- **page-break:** Insert page breaks between chapters. Defaults to `true`.
   190‚Üí
   191‚Üí### `[output.html.fold]`
   192‚Üí
   193‚ÜíThe `[output.html.fold]` table provides options for controlling folding of the chapter listing in the navigation sidebar.
   194‚Üí
   195‚Üí```toml
   196‚Üí[output.html.fold]
   197‚Üíenable = false    # whether or not to enable section folding
   198‚Üílevel = 0         # the depth to start folding
   199‚Üí```
   200‚Üí
   201‚Üí- **enable:** Enable section-folding. When off, all folds are open.
   202‚Üí  Defaults to `false`.
   203‚Üí- **level:** The higher the more folded regions are open. When level is 0, all
   204‚Üí  folds are closed. Defaults to `0`.
   205‚Üí
   206‚Üí### `[output.html.playground]`
   207‚Üí
   208‚ÜíThe `[output.html.playground]` table provides options for controlling Rust sample code blocks, and their integration with the [Rust Playground].
   209‚Üí
   210‚Üí[Rust Playground]: https://play.rust-lang.org/
   211‚Üí
   212‚Üí```toml
   213‚Üí[output.html.playground]
   214‚Üíeditable = false         # allows editing the source code
   215‚Üícopyable = true          # include the copy button for copying code snippets
   216‚Üícopy-js = true           # includes the JavaScript for the code editor
   217‚Üíline-numbers = false     # displays line numbers for editable code
   218‚Üírunnable = true          # displays a run button for rust code
   219‚Üí```
   220‚Üí
   221‚Üí- **editable:** Allow editing the source code. Defaults to `false`.
   222‚Üí- **copyable:** Display the copy button on code snippets. Defaults to `true`.
   223‚Üí- **copy-js:** Copy JavaScript files for the editor to the output directory.
   224‚Üí  Defaults to `true`.
   225‚Üí- **line-numbers:** Display line numbers on editable sections of code. Requires both `editable` and `copy-js` to be `true`. Defaults to `false`.
   226‚Üí- **runnable:** Displays a run button for rust code snippets. Changing this to `false` will disable the run in playground feature globally. Defaults to `true`.
   227‚Üí
   228‚Üí[Ace]: https://ace.c9.io/
   229‚Üí
   230‚Üí### `[output.html.code]`
   231‚Üí
   232‚ÜíThe `[output.html.code]` table provides options for controlling code blocks.
   233‚Üí
   234‚Üí```toml
   235‚Üí[output.html.code]
   236‚Üí# A prefix string per language (one or more chars).
   237‚Üí# Any line starting with whitespace+prefix is hidden.
   238‚Üíhidelines = { python = "~" }
   239‚Üí```
   240‚Üí
   241‚Üí- **hidelines:** A table that defines how [hidden code lines](../mdbook.md#hiding-code-lines) work for each language.
   242‚Üí  The key is the language and the value is a string that will cause code lines starting with that prefix to be hidden.
   243‚Üí
   244‚Üí### `[output.html.search]`
   245‚Üí
   246‚ÜíThe `[output.html.search]` table provides options for controlling the built-in text [search].
   247‚ÜímdBook must be compiled with the `search` feature enabled (on by default).
   248‚Üí
   249‚Üí[search]: ../../guide/reading.md#search
   250‚Üí
   251‚Üí```toml
   252‚Üí[output.html.search]
   253‚Üíenable = true            # enables the search feature
   254‚Üílimit-results = 30       # maximum number of search results
   255‚Üíteaser-word-count = 30   # number of words used for a search result teaser
   256‚Üíuse-boolean-and = true   # multiple search terms must all match
   257‚Üíboost-title = 2          # ranking boost factor for matches in headers
   258‚Üíboost-hierarchy = 1      # ranking boost factor for matches in page names
   259‚Üíboost-paragraph = 1      # ranking boost factor for matches in text
   260‚Üíexpand = true            # partial words will match longer terms
   261‚Üíheading-split-level = 3  # link results to heading levels
   262‚Üícopy-js = true           # include Javascript code for search
   263‚Üí```
   264‚Üí
   265‚Üí- **enable:** Enables the search feature. Defaults to `true`.
   266‚Üí- **limit-results:** The maximum number of search results. Defaults to `30`.
   267‚Üí- **teaser-word-count:** The number of words used for a search result teaser.
   268‚Üí  Defaults to `30`.
   269‚Üí- **use-boolean-and:** Define the logical link between multiple search words. If
   270‚Üí  true, all search words must appear in each result. Defaults to `false`.
   271‚Üí- **boost-title:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   272‚Üí  appears in the header. Defaults to `2`.
   273‚Üí- **boost-hierarchy:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   274‚Üí  appears in the hierarchy. The hierarchy contains all titles of the parent
   275‚Üí  documents and all parent headings. Defaults to `1`.
   276‚Üí- **boost-paragraph:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   277‚Üí  appears in the text. Defaults to `1`.
   278‚Üí- **expand:** True if search should match longer results e.g. search `micro`
   279‚Üí  should match `microwave`. Defaults to `true`.
   280‚Üí- **heading-split-level:** Search results will link to a section of the document
   281‚Üí  which contains the result. Documents are split into sections by headings this
   282‚Üí  level or less. Defaults to `3`. (`### This is a level 3 heading`)
   283‚Üí- **copy-js:** Copy JavaScript files for the search implementation to the output
   284‚Üí  directory. Defaults to `true`.
   285‚Üí
   286‚Üí#### `[output.html.search.chapter]`
   287‚Üí
   288‚ÜíThe [`output.html.search.chapter`] table provides the ability to modify search settings per chapter or directory. Each key is the path to the chapter source file or directory, and the value is a table of settings to apply to that path. This will merge recursively, with more specific paths taking precedence.
   289‚Üí
   290‚Üí```toml
   291‚Üí[output.html.search.chapter]
   292‚Üí# Disables search indexing for all chapters in the `appendix` directory.
   293‚Üí"appendix" = { enable = false }
   294‚Üí# Enables search indexing for just this one appendix chapter.
   295‚Üí"appendix/glossary.md" = { enable = true }
   296‚Üí```
   297‚Üí
   298‚Üí- **enable:** Enables or disables search indexing for the given chapters. Defaults to `true`. This does not override the overall `output.html.search.enable` setting; that must be `true` for any search functionality to be enabled. Be cautious when disabling indexing for chapters because that can potentially lead to user confusion when they search for terms and expect them to be found. This should only be used in exceptional circumstances where keeping the chapter in the index will cause issues with the quality of the search results.
   299‚Üí
   300‚Üí### `[output.html.redirect]`
   301‚Üí
   302‚ÜíThe `[output.html.redirect]` table provides a way to add redirects.
   303‚ÜíThis is useful when you move, rename, or remove a page to ensure that links to the old URL will go to the new location.
   304‚Üí
   305‚Üí```toml
   306‚Üí[output.html.redirect]
   307‚Üí"/appendices/bibliography.html" = "https://rustc-dev-guide.rust-lang.org/appendix/bibliography.html"
   308‚Üí"/other-installation-methods.html" = "../infra/other-installation-methods.html"
   309‚Üí
   310‚Üí# Fragment redirects also work.
   311‚Üí"/some-existing-page.html#old-fragment" = "some-existing-page.html#new-fragment"
   312‚Üí
   313‚Üí# Fragment redirects also work for deleted pages.
   314‚Üí"/old-page.html" = "new-page.html"
   315‚Üí"/old-page.html#old-fragment" = "new-page.html#new-fragment"
   316‚Üí```
   317‚Üí
   318‚ÜíThe table contains key-value pairs where the key is where the redirect file needs to be created, as an absolute path from the build directory, (e.g. `/appendices/bibliography.html`).
   319‚ÜíThe value can be any valid URI the browser should navigate to (e.g. `https://rust-lang.org/`, `/overview.html`, or `../bibliography.html`).
   320‚Üí
   321‚ÜíThis will generate an HTML page which will automatically redirect to the given location.
   322‚Üí
   323‚ÜíWhen fragment redirects are specified, the page must use JavaScript to redirect to the correct location. This is useful if you rename or move a section header. Fragment redirects work with existing pages and deleted pages.
   324‚Üí
   325‚Üí## Markdown renderer
   326‚Üí
   327‚ÜíThe Markdown renderer will run preprocessors and then output the resulting
   328‚ÜíMarkdown. This is mostly useful for debugging preprocessors, especially in
   329‚Üíconjunction with `mdbook test` to see the Markdown that `mdbook` is passing
   330‚Üíto `rustdoc`.
   331‚Üí
   332‚ÜíThe Markdown renderer is included with `mdbook` but disabled by default.
   333‚ÜíEnable it by adding an empty table to your `book.toml` as follows:
   334‚Üí
   335‚Üí```toml
   336‚Üí[output.markdown]
   337‚Üí```
   338‚Üí
   339‚ÜíThere are no configuration options for the Markdown renderer at this time;
   340‚Üíonly whether it is enabled or disabled.
   341‚Üí
   342‚ÜíSee [the preprocessors documentation](preprocessors.md) for how to
   343‚Üíspecify which preprocessors should run before the Markdown renderer.
format/example.rs
     1‚Üífn main() {
format/markdown.md
     1‚Üí# Markdown
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜímdBook's [parser](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark) adheres to the [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/) specification with some extensions described below.
     4‚ÜíYou can take a quick [tutorial](https://commonmark.org/help/tutorial/),
     5‚Üíor [try out](https://spec.commonmark.org/dingus/) CommonMark in real time. A complete Markdown overview is out of scope for 
     6‚Üíthis documentation, but below is a high level overview of some of the basics. For a more in-depth experience, check out the
     7‚Üí[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org).
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí## Text and paragraphs
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíText is rendered relatively predictably: 
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí```markdown
    14‚ÜíHere is a line of text.
    15‚Üí
    16‚ÜíThis is a new line.
    17‚Üí```
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíWill look like you might expect:
    20‚Üí
    21‚ÜíHere is a line of text.
    22‚Üí
    23‚ÜíThis is a new line.
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí## Headings
    26‚Üí
    27‚ÜíHeadings use the `#` marker and should be on a line by themselves. More `#` mean smaller headings:
    28‚Üí
    29‚Üí```markdown
    30‚Üí### A heading 
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíSome text.
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí#### A smaller heading 
    35‚Üí
    36‚ÜíMore text.
    37‚Üí```
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí### A heading 
    40‚Üí
    41‚ÜíSome text.
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí#### A smaller heading 
    44‚Üí
    45‚ÜíMore text.
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí## Lists
    48‚Üí
    49‚ÜíLists can be unordered or ordered. Ordered lists will order automatically:
    50‚Üí
    51‚Üí```markdown
    52‚Üí* milk
    53‚Üí* eggs
    54‚Üí* butter
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí1. carrots
    57‚Üí1. celery
    58‚Üí1. radishes
    59‚Üí```
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üí* milk
    62‚Üí* eggs
    63‚Üí* butter
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí1. carrots
    66‚Üí1. celery
    67‚Üí1. radishes
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üí## Links
    70‚Üí
    71‚ÜíLinking to a URL or local file is easy:
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üí```markdown
    74‚ÜíUse [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    75‚Üí
    76‚ÜíRead about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    77‚Üí
    78‚ÜíAnd now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    79‚Üí
    80‚ÜíA bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    83‚Üí```
    84‚Üí
    85‚ÜíUse [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    86‚Üí
    87‚ÜíRead about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    88‚Üí
    89‚ÜíAnd now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíA bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    94‚Üí----
    95‚Üí
    96‚ÜíRelative links that end with `.md` will be converted to the `.html` extension.
    97‚ÜíIt is recommended to use `.md` links when possible.
    98‚ÜíThis is useful when viewing the Markdown file outside of mdBook, for example on GitHub or GitLab which render Markdown automatically.
    99‚Üí
   100‚ÜíLinks to `README.md` will be converted to `index.html`.
   101‚ÜíThis is done since some services like GitHub render README files automatically, but web servers typically expect the root file to be called `index.html`.
   102‚Üí
   103‚ÜíYou can link to individual headings with `#` fragments.
   104‚ÜíFor example, `mdbook.md#text-and-paragraphs` would link to the [Text and Paragraphs](#text-and-paragraphs) section above.
   105‚ÜíThe ID is created by transforming the heading such as converting to lowercase and replacing spaces with dashes.
   106‚ÜíYou can click on any heading and look at the URL in your browser to see what the fragment looks like.
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí## Images
   109‚Üí
   110‚ÜíIncluding images is simply a matter of including a link to them, much like in the _Links_ section above. The following markdown
   111‚Üíincludes the Rust logo SVG image found in the `images` directory at the same level as this file:
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üí```markdown
   114‚Üí![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   115‚Üí```
   116‚Üí
   117‚ÜíProduces the following HTML when built with mdBook:
   118‚Üí
   119‚Üí```html
   120‚Üí<p><img src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust Logo" /></p>
   121‚Üí```
   122‚Üí
   123‚ÜíWhich, of course displays the image like so:
   124‚Üí
   125‚Üí![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   126‚Üí
   127‚Üí## Extensions
   128‚Üí
   129‚ÜímdBook has several extensions beyond the standard CommonMark specification.
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí### Strikethrough
   132‚Üí
   133‚ÜíText may be rendered with a horizontal line through the center by wrapping the
   134‚Üítext with one or two tilde characters on each side:
   135‚Üí
   136‚Üí```text
   137‚ÜíAn example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   138‚Üí```
   139‚Üí
   140‚ÜíThis example will render as:
   141‚Üí
   142‚Üí> An example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   143‚Üí
   144‚ÜíThis follows the [GitHub Strikethrough extension][strikethrough].
   145‚Üí
   146‚Üí### Footnotes
   147‚Üí
   148‚ÜíA footnote generates a small numbered link in the text which when clicked
   149‚Üítakes the reader to the footnote text at the bottom of the item. The footnote
   150‚Üílabel is written similarly to a link reference with a caret at the front. The
   151‚Üífootnote text is written like a link reference definition, with the text
   152‚Üífollowing the label. Example:
   153‚Üí
   154‚Üí```text
   155‚ÜíThis is an example of a footnote[^note].
   156‚Üí
   157‚Üí[^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   158‚Üí    towards the bottom.
   159‚Üí```
   160‚Üí
   161‚ÜíThis example will render as:
   162‚Üí
   163‚Üí> This is an example of a footnote[^note].
   164‚Üí>
   165‚Üí> [^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   166‚Üí>     towards the bottom.
   167‚Üí
   168‚ÜíThe footnotes are automatically numbered based on the order the footnotes are
   169‚Üíwritten.
   170‚Üí
   171‚Üí### Tables
   172‚Üí
   173‚ÜíTables can be written using pipes and dashes to draw the rows and columns of
   174‚Üíthe table. These will be translated to HTML table matching the shape. Example:
   175‚Üí
   176‚Üí```text
   177‚Üí| Header1 | Header2 |
   178‚Üí|---------|---------|
   179‚Üí| abc     | def     |
   180‚Üí```
   181‚Üí
   182‚ÜíThis example will render similarly to this:
   183‚Üí
   184‚Üí| Header1 | Header2 |
   185‚Üí|---------|---------|
   186‚Üí| abc     | def     |
   187‚Üí
   188‚ÜíSee the specification for the [GitHub Tables extension][tables] for more
   189‚Üídetails on the exact syntax supported.
   190‚Üí
   191‚Üí### Task lists
   192‚Üí
   193‚ÜíTask lists can be used as a checklist of items that have been completed.
   194‚ÜíExample:
   195‚Üí
   196‚Üí```md
   197‚Üí- [x] Complete task
   198‚Üí- [ ] Incomplete task
   199‚Üí```
   200‚Üí
   201‚ÜíThis will render as:
   202‚Üí
   203‚Üí> - [x] Complete task
   204‚Üí> - [ ] Incomplete task
   205‚Üí
   206‚ÜíSee the specification for the [task list extension] for more details.
   207‚Üí
   208‚Üí### Smart punctuation
   209‚Üí
   210‚ÜíSome ASCII punctuation sequences will be automatically turned into fancy Unicode
   211‚Üícharacters:
   212‚Üí
   213‚Üí| ASCII sequence | Unicode |
   214‚Üí|----------------|---------|
   215‚Üí| `--`           | ‚Äì       |
   216‚Üí| `---`          | ‚Äî       |
   217‚Üí| `...`          | ‚Ä¶       |
   218‚Üí| `"`            | ‚Äú or ‚Äù, depending on context |
   219‚Üí| `'`            | ‚Äò or ‚Äô, depending on context |
   220‚Üí
   221‚ÜíSo, no need to manually enter those Unicode characters!
   222‚Üí
   223‚ÜíThis feature is enabled by default.
   224‚ÜíTo disable it, see the [`output.html.smart-punctuation`] config option.
   225‚Üí
   226‚Üí[strikethrough]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#strikethrough-extension-
   227‚Üí[tables]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#tables-extension-
   228‚Üí[task list extension]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#task-list-items-extension-
   229‚Üí[`output.html.smart-punctuation`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   230‚Üí
   231‚Üí### Heading attributes
   232‚Üí
   233‚ÜíHeadings can have a custom HTML ID and classes. This lets you maintain the same ID even if you change the heading's text, it also lets you add multiple classes in the heading.
   234‚Üí
   235‚ÜíExample:
   236‚Üí```md
   237‚Üí# Example heading { #first .class1 .class2 }
   238‚Üí```
   239‚Üí
   240‚ÜíThis makes the level 1 heading with the content `Example heading`, ID `first`, and classes `class1` and `class2`. Note that the attributes should be space-separated.
   241‚Üí
   242‚ÜíMore information can be found in the [heading attrs spec page](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark/blob/master/pulldown-cmark/specs/heading_attrs.txt).
   243‚Üí
   244‚Üí### Definition lists
   245‚Üí
   246‚ÜíDefinition lists can be used for things like glossary entries. The term is listed on a line by itself, followed by one or more definitions. Each definition must begin with a `:` (after 0-2 spaces).
   247‚Üí
   248‚ÜíExample:
   249‚Üí
   250‚Üí```md
   251‚Üíterm A
   252‚Üí  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   253‚Üí    can span multiple lines.
   254‚Üí
   255‚Üíterm B
   256‚Üí  : This is a definition of term B.
   257‚Üí  : This has more than one definition.
   258‚Üí```
   259‚Üí
   260‚ÜíThis will render as:
   261‚Üí
   262‚Üíterm A
   263‚Üí  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   264‚Üí    can span multiple lines.
   265‚Üí
   266‚Üíterm B
   267‚Üí  : This is a definition of term B.
   268‚Üí  : This has more than one definition.
   269‚Üí
   270‚ÜíTerms are clickable just like headers, which will set the browser's URL to point directly to that term.
   271‚Üí
   272‚ÜíSee the [definition lists spec](https://github.com/pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark/blob/HEAD/pulldown-cmark/specs/definition_lists.txt) for more information on the specifics of the syntax. See the [Wikipedia guidelines for glossaries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Glossaries#General_guidelines_for_writing_glossaries) for some guidelines on how to write a glossary.
   273‚Üí
   274‚ÜíThis feature is enabled by default.
   275‚ÜíTo disable it, see the [`output.html.definition-lists`] config option.
   276‚Üí
   277‚Üí[`output.html.definition-lists`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   278‚Üí
   279‚Üí### Admonitions
   280‚Üí
   281‚ÜíAn admonition is a special type of callout or notice block used to highlight important information. It is written as a blockquote with a special tag on the first line.
   282‚Üí
   283‚Üí```md
   284‚Üí> [!NOTE]
   285‚Üí> General information or additional context.
   286‚Üí
   287‚Üí> [!TIP]
   288‚Üí> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   289‚Üí
   290‚Üí> [!IMPORTANT]
   291‚Üí> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   292‚Üí
   293‚Üí> [!WARNING]
   294‚Üí> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   295‚Üí
   296‚Üí> [!CAUTION]
   297‚Üí> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   298‚Üí```
   299‚Üí
   300‚ÜíThese will render as:
   301‚Üí
   302‚Üí> [!NOTE]
   303‚Üí> General information or additional context.
   304‚Üí
   305‚Üí> [!TIP]
   306‚Üí> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   307‚Üí
   308‚Üí> [!IMPORTANT]
   309‚Üí> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   310‚Üí
   311‚Üí> [!WARNING]
   312‚Üí> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   313‚Üí
   314‚Üí> [!CAUTION]
   315‚Üí> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   316‚Üí
   317‚ÜíThis feature is enabled by default.
   318‚ÜíTo disable it, see the [`output.html.admonitions`] config option.
   319‚Üí
   320‚Üí[`output.html.admonitions`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
format/mathjax.md
     1‚Üí# MathJax support
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜímdBook has optional support for math equations through
     4‚Üí[MathJax](https://www.mathjax.org/).
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíTo enable MathJax, you need to add the `mathjax-support` key to your `book.toml`
     7‚Üíunder the `output.html` section.
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí```toml
    10‚Üí[output.html]
    11‚Üímathjax-support = true
    12‚Üí```
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí>**Note:** The usual delimiters MathJax uses are not yet supported. You can't
    15‚Üícurrently use `$$ ... $$` as delimiters and the `\[ ... \]` delimiters need an
    16‚Üíextra backslash to work. Hopefully this limitation will be lifted soon.
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí>**Note:** When you use double backslashes in MathJax blocks (for example in
    19‚Üí> commands such as `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\ \frac 3 4 \end{cases}`) you need
    20‚Üí> to add _two extra_ backslashes (e.g., `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\\\ \frac 3 4
    21‚Üí> \end{cases}`).
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üí### Inline equations
    25‚ÜíInline equations are delimited by `\\(` and `\\)`. So for example, to render the
    26‚Üífollowing inline equation \\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\) you would write
    27‚Üíthe following:
    28‚Üí```
    29‚Üí\\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\)
    30‚Üí```
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí### Block equations
    33‚ÜíBlock equations are delimited by `\\[` and `\\]`. To render the following
    34‚Üíequation
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    37‚Üí
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üíyou would write:
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí```bash
    42‚Üí\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    43‚Üí```
format/mdbook.md
     1‚Üí# mdBook-specific features
     2‚Üí
     3‚Üí## Hiding code lines
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíThere is a feature in mdBook that lets you hide code lines by prepending them with a specific prefix.
     6‚Üí
     7‚ÜíFor the Rust language, you can prefix lines with `# ` (`#` followed by a space) to hide them [like you would with Rustdoc][rustdoc-hide].
     8‚ÜíThis prefix can be escaped with `##` to prevent the hiding of a line that should begin with the literal string `# ` (see [Rustdoc's docs][rustdoc-hide] for more details)
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí[rustdoc-hide]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/rustdoc/write-documentation/documentation-tests.html#hiding-portions-of-the-example
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí```bash
    13‚Üí# fn main() {
    14‚Üí    let x = 5;
    15‚Üí    let y = 6;
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí    println!("{}", x + y);
    18‚Üí# }
    19‚Üí```
    20‚Üí
    21‚ÜíWill render as
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí```rust
    24‚Üí# fn main() {
    25‚Üí    let x = 5;
    26‚Üí    let y = 6;
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí    println!("{}", x + y);
    29‚Üí# }
    30‚Üí```
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíWhen you tap or hover the mouse over the code block, there will be an eyeball icon (<i class="fa fa-eye"></i>) which will toggle the visibility of the hidden lines.
    33‚Üí
    34‚ÜíBy default, this only works for code examples that are annotated with `rust`.
    35‚ÜíHowever, you can define custom prefixes for other languages by adding a new line-hiding prefix in your `book.toml` with the language name and prefix character(s):
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí```toml
    38‚Üí[output.html.code.hidelines]
    39‚Üípython = "~"
    40‚Üí```
    41‚Üí
    42‚ÜíThe prefix will hide any lines that begin with the given prefix. With the python prefix shown above, this:
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí```bash
    45‚Üí~hidden()
    46‚Üínothidden():
    47‚Üí~    hidden()
    48‚Üí    ~hidden()
    49‚Üí    nothidden()
    50‚Üí```
    51‚Üí
    52‚Üíwill render as
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí```python
    55‚Üí~hidden()
    56‚Üínothidden():
    57‚Üí~    hidden()
    58‚Üí    ~hidden()
    59‚Üí    nothidden()
    60‚Üí```
    61‚Üí
    62‚ÜíThis behavior can be overridden locally with a different prefix. This has the same effect as above:
    63‚Üí
    64‚Üí~~~markdown
    65‚Üí```python,hidelines=!!!
    66‚Üí!!!hidden()
    67‚Üínothidden():
    68‚Üí!!!    hidden()
    69‚Üí    !!!hidden()
    70‚Üí    nothidden()
    71‚Üí```
    72‚Üí~~~
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí## Rust playground
    75‚Üí
    76‚ÜíRust language code blocks will automatically get a play button (<i class="fas fa-play"></i>) which will execute the code and display the output just below the code block.
    77‚ÜíThis works by sending the code to the [Rust Playground].
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí```rust
    80‚Üíprintln!("Hello, World!");
    81‚Üí```
    82‚Üí
    83‚ÜíIf there is no `main` function, then the code is automatically wrapped inside one.
    84‚Üí
    85‚ÜíIf you wish to disable the play button for a code block, you can include the `noplayground` option on the code block like this:
    86‚Üí
    87‚Üí~~~markdown
    88‚Üí```rust,noplayground
    89‚Üílet mut name = String::new();
    90‚Üístd::io::stdin().read_line(&mut name).expect("failed to read line");
    91‚Üíprintln!("Hello {}!", name);
    92‚Üí```
    93‚Üí~~~
    94‚Üí
    95‚ÜíOr, if you wish to disable the play button for all code blocks in your book, you can write the config to the `book.toml` like this.
    96‚Üí
    97‚Üí```toml
    98‚Üí[output.html.playground]
    99‚Üírunnable = false
   100‚Üí```
   101‚Üí
   102‚Üí## Rust code block attributes
   103‚Üí
   104‚ÜíAdditional attributes can be included in Rust code blocks with comma, space, or tab-separated terms just after the language term. For example:
   105‚Üí
   106‚Üí~~~markdown
   107‚Üí```rust,ignore
   108‚Üí# This example won't be tested.
   109‚Üípanic!("oops!");
   110‚Üí```
   111‚Üí~~~
   112‚Üí
   113‚ÜíThese are particularly important when using [`mdbook test`] to test Rust examples.
   114‚ÜíThese use the same attributes as [rustdoc attributes], with a few additions:
   115‚Üí
   116‚Üí* `editable` --- Enables the [editor].
   117‚Üí* `noplayground` --- Removes the play button, but will still be tested.
   118‚Üí* `mdbook-runnable` --- Forces the play button to be displayed.
   119‚Üí  This is intended to be combined with the `ignore` attribute for examples that should not be tested, but you want to allow the reader to run.
   120‚Üí* `ignore` --- Will not be tested and no play button is shown, but it is still highlighted as Rust syntax.
   121‚Üí* `should_panic` --- When executed, it should produce a panic.
   122‚Üí* `no_run` --- The code is compiled when tested, but it is not run.
   123‚Üí  The play button is also not shown.
   124‚Üí* `compile_fail` --- The code should fail to compile.
   125‚Üí* `edition2015`, `edition2018`, `edition2021`, `edition2024` --- Forces the use of a specific Rust edition.
   126‚Üí  See [`rust.edition`] to set this globally.
   127‚Üí
   128‚Üí[`mdbook test`]: ../cli/test.md
   129‚Üí[rustdoc attributes]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/documentation-tests.html#attributes
   130‚Üí[editor]: theme/editor.md
   131‚Üí[`rust.edition`]: configuration/general.md#rust-options
   132‚Üí
   133‚Üí## Including files
   134‚Üí
   135‚ÜíWith the following syntax, you can include files into your book:
   136‚Üí
   137‚Üí```hbs
   138‚Üí\{{#include file.rs}}
   139‚Üí```
   140‚Üí
   141‚ÜíThe path to the file has to be relative from the current source file.
   142‚Üí
   143‚ÜímdBook will interpret included files as Markdown. Since the include command
   144‚Üíis usually used for inserting code snippets and examples, you will often
   145‚Üíwrap the command with ```` ``` ```` to display the file contents without
   146‚Üíinterpreting them.
   147‚Üí
   148‚Üí````hbs
   149‚Üí```
   150‚Üí\{{#include file.rs}}
   151‚Üí```
   152‚Üí````
   153‚Üí
   154‚Üí## Including portions of a file
   155‚ÜíOften you only need a specific part of the file, e.g. relevant lines for an
   156‚Üíexample. We support four different modes of partial includes:
   157‚Üí
   158‚Üí```hbs
   159‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:2}}
   160‚Üí\{{#include file.rs::10}}
   161‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:2:}}
   162‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:2:10}}
   163‚Üí```
   164‚Üí
   165‚ÜíThe first command only includes the second line from file `file.rs`. The second
   166‚Üícommand includes all lines up to line 10, i.e. the lines from 11 till the end of
   167‚Üíthe file are omitted. The third command includes all lines from line 2, i.e. the
   168‚Üífirst line is omitted. The last command includes the excerpt of `file.rs`
   169‚Üíconsisting of lines 2 to 10.
   170‚Üí
   171‚ÜíTo avoid breaking your book when modifying included files, you can also
   172‚Üíinclude a specific section using anchors instead of line numbers.
   173‚ÜíAn anchor is a pair of matching lines. The line beginning an anchor must
   174‚Üímatch the regex `ANCHOR:\s*[\w_-]+` and similarly the ending line must match
   175‚Üíthe regex `ANCHOR_END:\s*[\w_-]+`. This allows you to put anchors in
   176‚Üíany kind of commented line.
   177‚Üí
   178‚ÜíConsider the following file to include:
   179‚Üí```rs
   180‚Üí/* ANCHOR: all */
   181‚Üí
   182‚Üí// ANCHOR: component
   183‚Üístruct Paddle {
   184‚Üí    hello: f32,
   185‚Üí}
   186‚Üí// ANCHOR_END: component
   187‚Üí
   188‚Üí////////// ANCHOR: system
   189‚Üíimpl System for MySystem { ... }
   190‚Üí////////// ANCHOR_END: system
   191‚Üí
   192‚Üí/* ANCHOR_END: all */
   193‚Üí```
   194‚Üí
   195‚ÜíThen in the book, all you have to do is:
   196‚Üí````hbs
   197‚ÜíHere is a component:
   198‚Üí```rust,no_run,noplayground
   199‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:component}}
   200‚Üí```
   201‚Üí
   202‚ÜíHere is a system:
   203‚Üí```rust,no_run,noplayground
   204‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:system}}
   205‚Üí```
   206‚Üí
   207‚ÜíThis is the full file.
   208‚Üí```rust,no_run,noplayground
   209‚Üí\{{#include file.rs:all}}
   210‚Üí```
   211‚Üí````
   212‚Üí
   213‚ÜíLines containing anchor patterns inside the included anchor are ignored.
   214‚Üí
   215‚Üí## Including a file but initially hiding all except specified lines
   216‚Üí
   217‚ÜíThe `rustdoc_include` helper is for including code from external Rust files that contain complete
   218‚Üíexamples, but only initially showing particular lines specified with line numbers or anchors in the
   219‚Üísame way as with `include`.
   220‚Üí
   221‚ÜíThe lines not in the line number range or between the anchors will still be included, but they will
   222‚Üíbe prefaced with `#`. This way, a reader can expand the snippet to see the complete example, and
   223‚ÜíRustdoc will use the complete example when you run `mdbook test`.
   224‚Üí
   225‚ÜíFor example, consider a file named `file.rs` that contains this Rust program:
   226‚Üí
   227‚Üí```rust
   228‚Üífn main() {
   229‚Üí    let x = add_one(2);
   230‚Üí    assert_eq!(x, 3);
   231‚Üí}
   232‚Üí
   233‚Üífn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   234‚Üí    num + 1
   235‚Üí}
   236‚Üí```
   237‚Üí
   238‚ÜíWe can include a snippet that initially shows only line 2 by using this syntax:
   239‚Üí
   240‚Üí````hbs
   241‚ÜíTo call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   242‚Üí
   243‚Üí```rust
   244‚Üí\{{#rustdoc_include file.rs:2}}
   245‚Üí```
   246‚Üí````
   247‚Üí
   248‚ÜíThis would have the same effect as if we had manually inserted the code and hidden all but line 2
   249‚Üíusing `#`:
   250‚Üí
   251‚Üí````hbs
   252‚ÜíTo call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   253‚Üí
   254‚Üí```rust
   255‚Üí# fn main() {
   256‚Üí    let x = add_one(2);
   257‚Üí#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   258‚Üí# }
   259‚Üí#
   260‚Üí# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   261‚Üí#     num + 1
   262‚Üí# }
   263‚Üí```
   264‚Üí````
   265‚Üí
   266‚ÜíThat is, it looks like this (click the "expand" icon to see the rest of the file):
   267‚Üí
   268‚Üí```rust
   269‚Üí# fn main() {
   270‚Üí    let x = add_one(2);
   271‚Üí#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   272‚Üí# }
   273‚Üí#
   274‚Üí# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   275‚Üí#     num + 1
   276‚Üí# }
   277‚Üí```
   278‚Üí
   279‚Üí## Inserting runnable Rust files
   280‚Üí
   281‚ÜíWith the following syntax, you can insert runnable Rust files into your book:
   282‚Üí
   283‚Üí```hbs
   284‚Üí\{{#playground file.rs}}
   285‚Üí```
   286‚Üí
   287‚ÜíThe path to the Rust file has to be relative from the current source file.
   288‚Üí
   289‚ÜíWhen play is clicked, the code snippet will be sent to the [Rust Playground] to be
   290‚Üícompiled and run. The result is sent back and displayed directly underneath the
   291‚Üícode.
   292‚Üí
   293‚ÜíHere is what a rendered code snippet looks like:
   294‚Üí
   295‚Üí{{#playground example.rs}}
   296‚Üí
   297‚ÜíAny additional values passed after the filename will be included as attributes of the code block.
   298‚ÜíFor example `\{{#playground example.rs editable}}` will create the code block like the following:
   299‚Üí
   300‚Üí~~~markdown
   301‚Üí```rust,editable
   302‚Üí# Contents of example.rs here.
   303‚Üí```
   304‚Üí~~~
   305‚Üí
   306‚ÜíAnd the `editable` attribute will enable the [editor] as described at [Rust code block attributes](#rust-code-block-attributes).
   307‚Üí
   308‚Üí[Rust Playground]: https://play.rust-lang.org/
   309‚Üí
   310‚Üí## Controlling page \<title\>
   311‚Üí
   312‚ÜíA chapter can set a \<title\> that is different from its entry in the table of
   313‚Üícontents (sidebar) by including a `\{{#title ...}}` near the top of the page.
   314‚Üí
   315‚Üí```hbs
   316‚Üí\{{#title My Title}}
   317‚Üí```
   318‚Üí
   319‚Üí## HTML classes provided by mdBook
   320‚Üí
   321‚Üí<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   322‚Üí
   323‚Üí### `class="left"` and `"right"`
   324‚Üí
   325‚ÜíThese classes are provided by default, for inline HTML to float images.
   326‚Üí
   327‚Üí```html
   328‚Üí<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   329‚Üí```
   330‚Üí
   331‚Üí### `class="hidden"`
   332‚Üí
   333‚ÜíHTML tags with class `hidden` will not be shown.
   334‚Üí
   335‚Üí```html
   336‚Üí<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   337‚Üí```
   338‚Üí
   339‚Üí<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   340‚Üí
   341‚Üí## Font-Awesome icons
   342‚Üí
   343‚ÜímdBook includes a copy of version 6 of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
   344‚ÜíMIT-licensed SVG files. It emulates the `<i>` syntax, but converts the results
   345‚Üíto inline SVG. Only the regular, solid, and brands icons are included; paid
   346‚Üífeatures like the light icons are not.
   347‚Üí
   348‚ÜíFor example, given this HTML syntax:
   349‚Üí
   350‚Üí```hbs
   351‚ÜíThe result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   352‚Üí```
   353‚Üí
   354‚ÜíThe result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   355‚Üí
   356‚ÜíSee the [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search) for the available icons.
format/summary.md
     1‚Üí# SUMMARY.md
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe summary file is used by mdBook to know what chapters to include, in what
     4‚Üíorder they should appear, what their hierarchy is and where the source files
     5‚Üíare. Without this file, there is no book.
     6‚Üí
     7‚ÜíThis markdown file must be named `SUMMARY.md`. Its formatting
     8‚Üíis very strict and must follow the structure outlined below to allow for easy
     9‚Üíparsing. Any element not specified below, be it formatting or textual, is likely
    10‚Üíto be ignored at best, or may cause an error when attempting to build the book.
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí### Structure
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí1. ***Title*** - While optional, it's common practice to begin with a title, generally <code
    15‚Üí   class="language-markdown"># Summary</code>. This is ignored by the parser however, and
    16‚Üí   can be omitted.
    17‚Üí   ```markdown
    18‚Üí   # Summary
    19‚Üí   ```
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí1. ***Prefix Chapter*** - Before the main numbered chapters, prefix chapters can be added
    22‚Üí   that will not be numbered. This is useful for forewords,
    23‚Üí   introductions, etc. There are, however, some constraints. Prefix chapters cannot be
    24‚Üí   nested; they should all be on the root level. And you cannot add
    25‚Üí   prefix chapters once you have added numbered chapters.
    26‚Üí   ```markdown
    27‚Üí   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    28‚Üí
    29‚Üí   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    30‚Üí   ```
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí1. ***Part Title*** -
    33‚Üí   Level 1 headers can be used as a title for the following numbered chapters.
    34‚Üí   This can be used to logically separate different sections of the book.
    35‚Üí   The title is rendered as unclickable text.
    36‚Üí   Titles are optional, and the numbered chapters can be broken into as many parts as desired.
    37‚Üí   Part titles must be h1 headers (one `#`), other heading levels are ignored.
    38‚Üí   ```markdown
    39‚Üí   # My Part Title
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    42‚Üí   ```
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí1. ***Numbered Chapter*** - Numbered chapters outline the main content of the book
    45‚Üí   and can be nested, resulting in a nice hierarchy
    46‚Üí   (chapters, sub-chapters, etc.).
    47‚Üí   ```markdown
    48‚Üí   # Title of Part
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    51‚Üí   - [Second Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    52‚Üí      - [Sub Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown3.md)
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí   # Title of Another Part
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí   - [Another Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown4.md)
    57‚Üí   ```
    58‚Üí   Numbered chapters can be denoted with either `-` or `*` (do not mix delimiters). 
    59‚Üí   
    60‚Üí1. ***Suffix Chapter*** - Like prefix chapters, suffix chapters are unnumbered, but they come after 
    61‚Üí   numbered chapters.
    62‚Üí   ```markdown
    63‚Üí   - [Last Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí   [Title of Suffix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    66‚Üí   ```
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí1. ***Draft chapters*** - Draft chapters are chapters without a file and thus content.
    69‚Üí   The purpose of a draft chapter is to signal future chapters still to be written.
    70‚Üí   Or when still laying out the structure of the book to avoid creating the files
    71‚Üí   while you are still changing the structure of the book a lot.
    72‚Üí   Draft chapters will be rendered in the HTML renderer as disabled links in the table
    73‚Üí   of contents, as you can see for the next chapter in the table of contents on the left.
    74‚Üí   Draft chapters are written like normal chapters but without writing the path to the file.
    75‚Üí   ```markdown
    76‚Üí   - [Draft Chapter]()
    77‚Üí   ```
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí1. ***Separators*** - Separators can be added before, in between, and after any other element. They result
    80‚Üí   in an HTML rendered line in the built table of contents.  A separator is
    81‚Üí   a line containing exclusively dashes and at least three of them: `---`.
    82‚Üí   ```markdown
    83‚Üí   # My Part Title
    84‚Üí   
    85‚Üí   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    86‚Üí
    87‚Üí   ---
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    90‚Üí   ```
    91‚Üí  
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí### Example
    94‚Üí
    95‚ÜíBelow is the markdown source for the `SUMMARY.md` for this guide, with the resulting table
    96‚Üíof contents as rendered to the left.
    97‚Üí
    98‚Üí```markdown
    99‚Üí{{#include ../SUMMARY.md}}
   100‚Üí```
format/theme/README.md
     1‚Üí# Theme
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe default renderer uses a [handlebars](https://handlebarsjs.com) template to
     4‚Üírender your markdown files and comes with a default theme included in the mdBook
     5‚Üíbinary.
     6‚Üí
     7‚ÜíThe theme is totally customizable, you can selectively replace every file from
     8‚Üíthe theme by your own by adding a `theme` directory next to `src` folder in your
     9‚Üíproject root. Create a new file with the name of the file you want to override
    10‚Üíand now that file will be used instead of the default file.
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíHere are the files you can override:
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí- **_index.hbs_** is the handlebars template.
    15‚Üí- **_head.hbs_** is appended to the HTML `<head>` section.
    16‚Üí- **_header.hbs_** content is appended on top of every book page.
    17‚Üí- **_css/_** contains the CSS files for styling the book.
    18‚Üí    - **_css/chrome.css_** is for UI elements.
    19‚Üí    - **_css/general.css_** is the base styles.
    20‚Üí    - **_css/print.css_** is the style for printer output.
    21‚Üí    - **_css/variables.css_** contains variables used in other CSS files.
    22‚Üí- **_book.js_** is mostly used to add client side functionality, like hiding /
    23‚Üí  un-hiding the sidebar, changing the theme, ...
    24‚Üí- **_highlight.js_** is the JavaScript that is used to highlight code snippets,
    25‚Üí  you should not need to modify this.
    26‚Üí- **_highlight.css_** is the theme used for the code highlighting.
    27‚Üí- **_favicon.svg_** and **_favicon.png_** the favicon that will be used. The SVG
    28‚Üí  version is used by [newer browsers].
    29‚Üí- **fonts/fonts.css** contains the definition of which fonts to load.
    30‚Üí  Custom fonts can be included in the `fonts` directory.
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíGenerally, when you want to tweak the theme, you don't need to override all the
    33‚Üífiles. If you only need changes in the stylesheet, there is no point in
    34‚Üíoverriding all the other files. Because custom files take precedence over
    35‚Üíbuilt-in ones, they will not get updated with new fixes / features.
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí**Note:** When you override a file, it is possible that you break some
    38‚Üífunctionality. Therefore I recommend to use the file from the default theme as
    39‚Üítemplate and only add / modify what you need. You can copy the default theme
    40‚Üíinto your source directory automatically by using `mdbook init --theme` and just
    41‚Üíremove the files you don't want to override.
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí`mdbook init --theme` will not create every file listed above.
    44‚ÜíSome files, such as `head.hbs`, do not have built-in equivalents.
    45‚ÜíJust create the file if you need it.
    46‚Üí
    47‚ÜíIf you completely replace all built-in themes, be sure to also set
    48‚Üí[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`] in the config, which defaults to the
    49‚Üíbuilt-in `navy` theme.
    50‚Üí
    51‚Üí[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`]: ../configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
    52‚Üí[newer browsers]: https://caniuse.com/#feat=link-icon-svg
format/theme/editor.md
     1‚Üí# Editor
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíIn addition to providing runnable code playgrounds, mdBook optionally allows them
     4‚Üíto be editable. In order to enable editable code blocks, the following needs to
     5‚Üíbe added to the ***book.toml***:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```toml
     8‚Üí[output.html.playground]
     9‚Üíeditable = true
    10‚Üí```
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíAfter enabling editable code blocks, the `editable` attribute must be added to a
    13‚Üícode block to make it editable:
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí~~~markdown
    16‚Üí```rust,editable
    17‚Üífn main() {
    18‚Üí    let number = 5;
    19‚Üí    print!("{}", number);
    20‚Üí}
    21‚Üí```
    22‚Üí~~~
    23‚Üí
    24‚ÜíThe above will result in this editable playground:
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí```rust,editable
    27‚Üífn main() {
    28‚Üí    let number = 5;
    29‚Üí    print!("{}", number);
    30‚Üí}
    31‚Üí```
    32‚Üí
    33‚ÜíNote the new `Undo Changes` button in the editable playgrounds.
    34‚Üí
    35‚Üí## Customizing the editor
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíBy default, the editor is the [Ace](https://ace.c9.io/) editor, but, if desired,
    38‚Üíthe functionality may be overridden by providing a different folder:
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí```toml
    41‚Üí[output.html.playground]
    42‚Üíeditable = true
    43‚Üíeditor = "/path/to/editor"
    44‚Üí```
    45‚Üí
    46‚ÜíNote that for the editor changes to function correctly, the `book.js` inside of
    47‚Üíthe `theme` folder will need to be overridden as it has some couplings with the
    48‚Üídefault Ace editor.
format/theme/index-hbs.md
     1‚Üí# index.hbs
     2‚Üí
     3‚Üí`index.hbs` is the handlebars template that is used to render the book. The
     4‚Üímarkdown files are processed to html and then injected in that template.
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíIf you want to change the layout or style of your book, chances are that you
     7‚Üíwill have to modify this template a little bit. Here is what you need to know.
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí## Data
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíA lot of data is exposed to the handlebars template with the "context". In the
    12‚Üíhandlebars template you can access this information by using
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí```handlebars
    15‚Üí{{name_of_property}}
    16‚Üí```
    17‚Üí
    18‚ÜíHere is a list of the properties that are exposed:
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí- ***language*** Language of the book in the form `en`, as specified in `book.toml` (if not specified, defaults to `en`). To use in <code
    21‚Üí  class="language-html">\<html lang=\"{{ language }}\"></code> for example.
    22‚Üí- ***title*** Title used for the current page. This is identical to `{{ chapter_title }} - {{ book_title }}` unless `book_title` is not set in which case it just defaults to the `chapter_title`.
    23‚Üí- ***book_title*** Title of the book, as specified in `book.toml`
    24‚Üí- ***chapter_title*** Title of the current chapter, as listed in `SUMMARY.md`
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí- ***path*** Relative path to the original markdown file from the source
    27‚Üí  directory
    28‚Üí- ***content*** This is the rendered markdown.
    29‚Üí- ***path_to_root*** This is a path containing exclusively `../`'s that points
    30‚Üí  to the root of the book from the current file. Since the original directory
    31‚Üí  structure is maintained, it is useful to prepend relative links with this
    32‚Üí  `path_to_root`.
    33‚Üí- ***previous*** and ***next*** These are objects used for linking to the previous and next chapter. They contain the properties `title` and `link` of the corresponding chapter.
    34‚Üí- ***chapters*** Is an array of dictionaries of the form
    35‚Üí  ```json
    36‚Üí  {"section": "1.2.1", "name": "name of this chapter", "path": "dir/markdown.md"}
    37‚Üí  ```
    38‚Üí  containing all the chapters of the book. It is used for example to construct
    39‚Üí  the table of contents (sidebar).
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí## Handlebars helpers
    42‚Üí
    43‚ÜíIn addition to the properties you can access, there are some handlebars helpers
    44‚Üíat your disposal.
    45‚Üí
    46‚Üí### toc
    47‚Üí
    48‚ÜíThe toc helper is used like this
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí```handlebars
    51‚Üí{{#toc}}{{/toc}}
    52‚Üí```
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üíand outputs something that looks like this, depending on the structure of your
    55‚Üíbook
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí```html
    58‚Üí<ul class="chapter">
    59‚Üí    <li><a href="link/to/file.html">Some chapter</a></li>
    60‚Üí    <li>
    61‚Üí        <ul class="section">
    62‚Üí            <li><a href="link/to/other_file.html">Some other Chapter</a></li>
    63‚Üí        </ul>
    64‚Üí    </li>
    65‚Üí</ul>
    66‚Üí```
    67‚Üí
    68‚ÜíIf you would like to make a toc with another structure, you have access to the
    69‚Üíchapters property containing all the data. The only limitation at the moment
    70‚Üíis that you would have to do it with JavaScript instead of with a handlebars
    71‚Üíhelper.
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üí```html
    74‚Üí<script>
    75‚Üívar chapters = {{chapters}};
    76‚Üí// Processing here
    77‚Üí</script>
    78‚Üí```
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí### resource
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíThe path to a static file.
    83‚ÜíIt implicitly includes `path_to_root`,
    84‚Üíand accounts for files that are renamed with a hash in their filename.
    85‚Üí
    86‚Üí```handlebars
    87‚Üí<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ resource "css/chrome.css" }}">
    88‚Üí```
    89‚Üí
    90‚Üí### fa
    91‚Üí
    92‚ÜímdBook includes a copy of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
    93‚ÜíMIT-licensed SVG files. It accepts three positional arguments:
    94‚Üí
    95‚Üí1. Type: one of "solid", "regular", and "brands" (light and duotone are not
    96‚Üí   currently supported)
    97‚Üí2. Icon: anything chosen from the
    98‚Üí   [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search)
    99‚Üí3. ID (optional): if included, an HTML ID attribute will be added to the
   100‚Üí   icon's wrapping `<span>` tag
   101‚Üí
   102‚ÜíFor example, this handlebars syntax will become this HTML:
   103‚Üí
   104‚Üí```handlebars
   105‚Üí{{fa "solid" "print" "print-button"}}
   106‚Üí```
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí```html
   109‚Üí<span class=fa-svg id="print-button"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 512 512"><path d="M448 192V77.25c0-8.49-3.37-16.62-9.37-22.63L393.37 9.37c-6-6-14.14-9.37-22.63-9.37H96C78.33 0 64 14.33 64 32v160c-35.35 0-64 28.65-64 64v112c0 8.84 7.16 16 16 16h48v96c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32h320c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v-96h48c8.84 0 16-7.16 16-16V256c0-35.35-28.65-64-64-64zm-64 256H128v-96h256v96zm0-224H128V64h192v48c0 8.84 7.16 16 16 16h48v96zm48 72c-13.25 0-24-10.75-24-24 0-13.26 10.75-24 24-24s24 10.74 24 24c0 13.25-10.75 24-24 24z"/></svg></span>
   110‚Üí```
format/theme/syntax-highlighting.md
     1‚Üí# Syntax highlighting
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜímdBook uses [Highlight.js](https://highlightjs.org) with a custom theme
     4‚Üífor syntax highlighting.
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíAutomatic language detection has been turned off, so you will probably want to
     7‚Üíspecify the programming language you use like this:
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí~~~markdown
    10‚Üí```rust
    11‚Üífn main() {
    12‚Üí    // Some code
    13‚Üí}
    14‚Üí```
    15‚Üí~~~
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí## Supported languages
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíThese languages are supported by default, but you can add more by supplying
    20‚Üíyour own `highlight.js` file:
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí- apache
    23‚Üí- armasm
    24‚Üí- bash
    25‚Üí- c
    26‚Üí- coffeescript
    27‚Üí- cpp
    28‚Üí- csharp
    29‚Üí- css
    30‚Üí- d
    31‚Üí- diff
    32‚Üí- go
    33‚Üí- handlebars
    34‚Üí- haskell
    35‚Üí- http
    36‚Üí- ini
    37‚Üí- java
    38‚Üí- javascript
    39‚Üí- json
    40‚Üí- julia
    41‚Üí- kotlin
    42‚Üí- less
    43‚Üí- lua
    44‚Üí- makefile
    45‚Üí- markdown
    46‚Üí- nginx
    47‚Üí- nim
    48‚Üí- nix
    49‚Üí- objectivec
    50‚Üí- perl
    51‚Üí- php
    52‚Üí- plaintext
    53‚Üí- properties
    54‚Üí- python
    55‚Üí- r
    56‚Üí- ruby
    57‚Üí- rust
    58‚Üí- scala
    59‚Üí- scss
    60‚Üí- shell
    61‚Üí- sql
    62‚Üí- swift
    63‚Üí- typescript
    64‚Üí- x86asm
    65‚Üí- xml
    66‚Üí- yaml
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí## Custom theme
    69‚ÜíLike the rest of the theme, the files used for syntax highlighting can be
    70‚Üíoverridden with your own.
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí- ***highlight.js*** normally you shouldn't have to overwrite this file, unless
    73‚Üí  you want to use a more recent version.
    74‚Üí- ***highlight.css*** theme used by highlight.js for syntax highlighting.
    75‚Üí
    76‚ÜíIf you want to use another theme for `highlight.js` download it from their
    77‚Üíwebsite, or make it yourself, rename it to `highlight.css` and put it in
    78‚Üíthe `theme` folder of your book.
    79‚Üí
    80‚ÜíNow your theme will be used instead of the default theme.
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí## Improve default theme
    83‚Üí
    84‚ÜíIf you think the default theme doesn't look quite right for a specific language,
    85‚Üíor could be improved, feel free to [submit a new
    86‚Üíissue](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues) explaining what you
    87‚Üíhave in mind and I will take a look at it.
    88‚Üí
    89‚ÜíYou could also create a pull-request with the proposed improvements.
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíOverall the theme should be light and sober, without too many flashy colors.
guide/README.md
     1‚Üí# User guide
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThis user guide provides an introduction to basic concepts of using mdBook.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí- [Installation](installation.md)
     6‚Üí- [Reading Books](reading.md)
     7‚Üí- [Creating a Book](creating.md)
guide/creating.md
     1‚Üí# Creating a book
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíOnce you have the `mdbook` CLI tool installed, you can use it to create and render a book.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí## Initializing a book
     6‚Üí
     7‚ÜíThe `mdbook init` command will create a new directory containing an empty book for you to get started.
     8‚ÜíGive it the name of the directory that you want to create:
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí```sh
    11‚Üímdbook init my-first-book
    12‚Üí```
    13‚Üí
    14‚ÜíIt will ask a few questions before generating the book.
    15‚ÜíAfter answering the questions, you can change the current directory into the new book:
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí```sh
    18‚Üícd my-first-book
    19‚Üí```
    20‚Üí
    21‚ÜíThere are several ways to render a book, but one of the easiest methods is to use the `serve` command, which will build your book and start a local webserver:
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí```sh
    24‚Üímdbook serve --open
    25‚Üí```
    26‚Üí
    27‚ÜíThe `--open` option will open your default web browser to view your new book.
    28‚ÜíYou can leave the server running even while you edit the content of the book, and `mdbook` will automatically rebuild the output *and* automatically refresh your web browser.
    29‚Üí
    30‚ÜíCheck out the [CLI Guide](../cli/index.html) for more information about other `mdbook` commands and CLI options.
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí## Anatomy of a book
    33‚Üí
    34‚ÜíA book is built from several files which define the settings and layout of the book.
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí### `book.toml`
    37‚Üí
    38‚ÜíIn the root of your book, there is a `book.toml` file which contains settings for describing how to build your book.
    39‚ÜíThis is written in the [TOML markup language](https://toml.io/).
    40‚ÜíThe default settings are usually good enough to get you started.
    41‚ÜíWhen you are interested in exploring more features and options that mdBook provides, check out the [Configuration chapter](../format/configuration/index.html) for more details.
    42‚Üí
    43‚ÜíA very basic `book.toml` can be as simple as this:
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí```toml
    46‚Üí[book]
    47‚Üítitle = "My First Book"
    48‚Üí```
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí### `SUMMARY.md`
    51‚Üí
    52‚ÜíThe next major part of a book is the summary file located at `src/SUMMARY.md`.
    53‚ÜíThis file contains a list of all the chapters in the book.
    54‚ÜíBefore a chapter can be viewed, it must be added to this list.
    55‚Üí
    56‚ÜíHere's a basic summary file with a few chapters:
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí```md
    59‚Üí# Summary
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üí[Introduction](README.md)
    62‚Üí
    63‚Üí- [My First Chapter](my-first-chapter.md)
    64‚Üí- [Nested example](nested/README.md)
    65‚Üí    - [Sub-chapter](nested/sub-chapter.md)
    66‚Üí```
    67‚Üí
    68‚ÜíTry opening up `src/SUMMARY.md` in your editor and adding a few chapters.
    69‚ÜíIf any of the chapter files do not exist, `mdbook` will automatically create them for you.
    70‚Üí
    71‚ÜíFor more details on other formatting options for the summary file, check out the [Summary chapter](../format/summary.md).
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üí### Source files
    74‚Üí
    75‚ÜíThe content of your book is all contained in the `src` directory.
    76‚ÜíEach chapter is a separate Markdown file.
    77‚ÜíTypically, each chapter starts with a level 1 heading with the title of the chapter.
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí```md
    80‚Üí# My First Chapter
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíFill out your content here.
    83‚Üí```
    84‚Üí
    85‚ÜíThe precise layout of the files is up to you.
    86‚ÜíThe organization of the files will correspond to the HTML files generated, so keep in mind that the file layout is part of the URL of each chapter.
    87‚Üí
    88‚ÜíWhile the `mdbook serve` command is running, you can open any of the chapter files and start editing them.
    89‚ÜíEach time you save the file, `mdbook` will rebuild the book and refresh your web browser.
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíCheck out the [Markdown chapter](../format/markdown.md) for more information on formatting the content of your chapters.
    92‚Üí
    93‚ÜíAll other files in the `src` directory will be included in the output.
    94‚ÜíSo if you have images or other static files, just include them somewhere in the `src` directory.
    95‚Üí
    96‚Üí## Publishing a book
    97‚Üí
    98‚ÜíOnce you've written your book, you may want to host it somewhere for others to view.
    99‚ÜíThe first step is to build the output of the book.
   100‚ÜíThis can be done with the `mdbook build` command in the same directory where the `book.toml` file is located:
   101‚Üí
   102‚Üí```sh
   103‚Üímdbook build
   104‚Üí```
   105‚Üí
   106‚ÜíThis will generate a directory named `book` which contains the HTML content of your book.
   107‚ÜíYou can then place this directory on any web server to host it.
   108‚Üí
   109‚ÜíFor more information about publishing and deploying, check out the [Continuous Integration chapter](../continuous-integration.md) for more.
guide/installation.md
     1‚Üí# Installation
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThere are multiple ways to install the mdBook CLI tool.
     4‚ÜíChoose any one of the methods below that best suit your needs.
     5‚ÜíIf you are installing mdBook for automatic deployment, check out the [continuous integration] chapter for more examples on how to install.
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí[continuous integration]: ../continuous-integration.md
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí## Pre-compiled binaries
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíExecutable binaries are available for download on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    12‚ÜíDownload the binary for your platform (Windows, macOS, or Linux) and extract the archive.
    13‚ÜíThe archive contains an `mdbook` executable which you can run to build your books.
    14‚Üí
    15‚ÜíTo make it easier to run, put the path to the binary into your `PATH`.
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí[releases]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üí## Build from source using Rust
    20‚Üí
    21‚ÜíTo build the `mdbook` executable from source, you will first need to install Rust and Cargo.
    22‚ÜíFollow the instructions on the [Rust installation page].
    23‚ÜímdBook currently requires at least Rust version 1.88.
    24‚Üí
    25‚ÜíOnce you have installed Rust, the following command can be used to build and install mdBook:
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí```sh
    28‚Üícargo install mdbook
    29‚Üí```
    30‚Üí
    31‚ÜíThis will automatically download mdBook from [crates.io], build it, and install it in Cargo's global binary directory (`~/.cargo/bin/` by default).
    32‚Üí
    33‚ÜíYou can run `cargo install mdbook` again whenever you want to update to a new version.
    34‚ÜíThat command will check if there is a newer version, and re-install mdBook if a newer version is found.
    35‚Üí
    36‚ÜíTo uninstall, run the command `cargo uninstall mdbook`.
    37‚Üí
    38‚Üí[Rust installation page]: https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install
    39‚Üí[crates.io]: https://crates.io/
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí### Installing the latest master version
    42‚Üí
    43‚ÜíThe version published to crates.io will ever so slightly be behind the version hosted on GitHub.
    44‚ÜíIf you need the latest version you can build the git version of mdBook yourself.
    45‚ÜíCargo makes this ***super easy***!
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí```sh
    48‚Üícargo install --git https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook.git mdbook
    49‚Üí```
    50‚Üí
    51‚ÜíAgain, make sure to add the Cargo bin directory to your `PATH`.
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üí## Modifying and contributing
    54‚Üí
    55‚ÜíIf you are interested in making modifications to mdBook itself, check out the [Contributing Guide] for more information.
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí[Contributing Guide]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
guide/reading.md
     1‚Üí# Reading books
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThis chapter gives an introduction on how to interact with a book produced by mdBook.
     4‚ÜíThis assumes you are reading an HTML book.
     5‚ÜíThe options and formatting will be different for other output formats such as PDF.
     6‚Üí
     7‚ÜíA book is organized into *chapters*.
     8‚ÜíEach chapter is a separate page.
     9‚ÜíChapters can be nested into a hierarchy of sub-chapters.
    10‚ÜíTypically, each chapter will be organized into a series of *headings* to subdivide a chapter.
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí## Navigation
    13‚Üí
    14‚ÜíThere are several methods for navigating through the chapters of a book.
    15‚Üí
    16‚ÜíThe **sidebar** on the left provides a list of all chapters.
    17‚ÜíClicking on any of the chapter titles will load that page.
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíThe sidebar may not automatically appear if the window is too narrow, particularly on mobile displays.
    20‚ÜíIn that situation, the menu icon (three horizontal bars) at the top-left of the page can be pressed to open and close the sidebar.
    21‚Üí
    22‚ÜíThe **arrow buttons** at the bottom of the page can be used to navigate to the previous or the next chapter.
    23‚Üí
    24‚ÜíThe **left and right arrow keys** on the keyboard can be used to navigate to the previous or the next chapter.
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí## Top menu bar
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíThe menu bar at the top of the page provides some icons for interacting with the book.
    29‚ÜíThe icons displayed will depend on the settings of how the book was generated.
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí| Icon | Description |
    32‚Üí|------|-------------|
    33‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-bars"></i> | Opens and closes the chapter listing sidebar. |
    34‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-paintbrush"></i> | Opens a picker to choose a different color theme. |
    35‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-magnifying-glass"></i> | Opens a search bar for searching within the book. |
    36‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-print"></i> | Instructs the web browser to print the entire book. |
    37‚Üí| <i class="fab fa-github"></i> | Opens a link to the website that hosts the source code of the book. |
    38‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-pencil"></i> | Opens a page to directly edit the source of the page you are currently reading. |
    39‚Üí
    40‚ÜíTapping the menu bar will scroll the page to the top.
    41‚Üí
    42‚Üí## Search
    43‚Üí
    44‚ÜíEach book has a built-in search system.
    45‚ÜíPressing the search icon <i class="fas fa-magnifying-glass"></i> in the menu bar, or pressing the <kbd>/</kbd> or <kbd>S</kbd> key on the keyboard will open an input box for entering search terms.
    46‚ÜíTyping some terms will show matching chapters and sections in real time.
    47‚Üí
    48‚ÜíClicking any of the results will jump to that section.
    49‚ÜíThe up and down arrow keys can be used to navigate the results, and enter will open the highlighted section.
    50‚Üí
    51‚ÜíAfter loading a search result, the matching search terms will be highlighted in the text.
    52‚ÜíClicking a highlighted word or pressing the <kbd>Escape</kbd> key will remove the highlighting.
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí## Code blocks
    55‚Üí
    56‚ÜímdBook books are often used for programming projects, and thus support highlighting code blocks and samples.
    57‚ÜíCode blocks may contain several different icons for interacting with them:
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üí| Icon | Description |
    60‚Üí|------|-------------|
    61‚Üí| <i class="fa fa-copy"></i> | Copies the code block into your local clipboard, to allow pasting into another application. |
    62‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-play"></i> | For Rust code examples, this will execute the sample code and display the compiler output just below the example (see [playground]). |
    63‚Üí| <i class="fa fa-eye"></i> | For Rust code examples, this will toggle visibility of "hidden" lines. Sometimes, larger examples will hide lines which are not particularly relevant to what is being illustrated (see [hiding code lines]). |
    64‚Üí| <i class="fas fa-clock-rotate-left"></i> | For [editable code examples][editor], this will undo any changes you have made. |
    65‚Üí
    66‚ÜíHere's an example:
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí```rust
    69‚Üíprintln!("Hello, World!");
    70‚Üí```
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí[editor]: ../format/theme/editor.md
    73‚Üí[playground]: ../format/mdbook.md#rust-playground
    74‚Üí[hiding code lines]: ../format/mdbook.md#hiding-code-lines
